1
00:02:43,863 --> 00:02:46,696
<i>The hills are alive</i>

2
00:02:46,866 --> 00:02:51,132
<i>With the sound of music</i>

3
00:02:51,638 --> 00:02:53,970
<i>With songs they have sung</i>

4
00:02:54,140 --> 00:02:58,839
<i>For a thousand years</i>

5
00:02:59,379 --> 00:03:02,405
<i>The hills fill my heart</i>

6
00:03:02,582 --> 00:03:07,007
<i>With the sound of music</i>

7
00:03:07,654 --> 00:03:14,344
<i>My heart wants to sing
Every song it hears</i>

8
00:03:15,295 --> 00:03:20,085
<i>My heart wants to beat like the wings
Of the birds that rise</i>

9
00:03:20,366 --> 00:03:23,290
<i>From the lake to the trees</i>

10
00:03:23,836 --> 00:03:28,000
<i>My heart wants to sigh
Like a chime that flies</i>

11
00:03:28,174 --> 00:03:31,996
<i>From a church on a breeze</i>

12
00:03:32,579 --> 00:03:35,935
<i>To laugh like a brook
When it trips and falls</i>

13
00:03:36,216 --> 00:03:39,549
<i>Over stones on its way</i>

14
00:03:40,019 --> 00:03:43,511
<i>To sing through the night</i>

15
00:03:43,690 --> 00:03:47,888
<i>Like a lark who is learning to pray</i>

16
00:03:48,094 --> 00:03:53,452
<i>I go to the hills</i>

17
00:03:54,133 --> 00:03:59,958
<i>When my heart is lonely</i>

18
00:04:00,540 --> 00:04:03,395
<i>I know I will hear</i>

19
00:04:03,576 --> 00:04:08,866
<i>What I've heard before</i>

20
00:04:09,449 --> 00:04:13,408
<i>My heart will be blessed</i>

21
00:04:14,354 --> 00:04:22,113
<i>With the sound of music</i>

22
00:04:23,229 --> 00:04:28,257
<i>And I'll sing</i>

23
00:04:28,501 --> 00:04:37,466
<i>Once more</i>

24
00:09:19,525 --> 00:09:24,224
<i>Hallelujah, hallelujah</i>

25
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:29,357
<i>Hallelujah, hallelujah</i>

26
00:09:31,837 --> 00:09:33,725
- Reverend Mother.
- Sister Bernice.

27
00:09:34,006 --> 00:09:36,566
- I simply cannot find her.
- Maria?

28
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:39,007
She's missing again.

29
00:09:39,879 --> 00:09:42,268
We should've put a cowbell
around her neck.

30
00:09:42,548 --> 00:09:45,574
Have you tried the barn? You know
how much she adores the animals.

31
00:09:45,851 --> 00:09:48,581
I have looked everywhere.
In all of the usual places.

32
00:09:48,788 --> 00:09:51,052
Sister, considering it's Maria...

33
00:09:51,290 --> 00:09:53,918
...I suggest you look in someplace
unusual.

34
00:09:59,231 --> 00:10:00,459
Well, Reverend Mother...

35
00:10:00,733 --> 00:10:03,361
...I hope this new infraction ends
whatever doubts...

36
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:06,868
...you may still have
about Maria's future here.

37
00:10:07,073 --> 00:10:11,100
I always try to keep faith
in my doubts, Sister Berthe.

38
00:10:11,377 --> 00:10:14,232
After all, the wool of a black sheep
is just as warm.

39
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:18,769
We are not talking about sheep,
black or white, Sister Margaretta.

40
00:10:19,051 --> 00:10:22,441
Of all the candidates for
the novitiate, Maria is the least--

41
00:10:22,722 --> 00:10:25,247
Children, children.

42
00:10:25,725 --> 00:10:29,684
We were speculating about
the qualifications of our postulants.

43
00:10:30,296 --> 00:10:33,288
The Mistress of Novices
and the Mistress of Postulants...

44
00:10:33,566 --> 00:10:38,822
...were trying to help me
by expressing opposite points of view.

45
00:10:39,105 --> 00:10:42,131
Tell me, Sister Catherine,
what do you think of Maria?

46
00:10:42,341 --> 00:10:44,468
She's a wonderful girl,
some of the time.

47
00:10:46,746 --> 00:10:49,476
- Sister Agatha?
- It's very easy to like Maria...

48
00:10:49,749 --> 00:10:52,274
...except when it's difficult.

49
00:10:52,518 --> 00:10:56,113
- And you, Sister Sophia?
- Oh, I love her very dearly.

50
00:10:56,322 --> 00:10:59,246
But she always seems to be
in trouble, doesn't she?

51
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:01,255
Exactly what I say.

52
00:11:01,627 --> 00:11:03,993
<i>She climbs a tree and scrapes her knee</i>

53
00:11:04,163 --> 00:11:05,960
<i>Her dress has got a tear</i>

54
00:11:06,599 --> 00:11:10,763
<i>She waltzes on her way to Mass
And whistles on the stair</i>

55
00:11:11,437 --> 00:11:15,862
<i>And underneath her wimple
She has curlers in her hair</i>

56
00:11:16,175 --> 00:11:20,805
<i>I've even heard her singing
In the abbey</i>

57
00:11:21,013 --> 00:11:23,004
<i>She's always late for chapel</i>

58
00:11:23,249 --> 00:11:25,513
<i>But her penitence is real</i>

59
00:11:25,818 --> 00:11:28,150
<i>She's always late for everything</i>

60
00:11:28,354 --> 00:11:30,379
<i>Except for every meal</i>

61
00:11:30,856 --> 00:11:35,486
<i>I hate to have to say it
But I very firmly feel</i>

62
00:11:35,795 --> 00:11:40,152
<i>Maria's not an asset to the abbey</i>

63
00:11:40,700 --> 00:11:43,191
<i>I'd like to say a word in her behalf</i>

64
00:11:43,402 --> 00:11:44,767
Say it, Sister Margaretta.

65
00:11:45,638 --> 00:11:49,028
<i>Maria makes me laugh</i>

66
00:11:52,545 --> 00:11:55,776
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

67
00:11:56,716 --> 00:12:00,208
<i>How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?</i>

68
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:04,076
<i>How do you find a word
That means Maria?</i>

69
00:12:04,590 --> 00:12:05,716
<i>A flibbertigibbet</i>

70
00:12:05,925 --> 00:12:07,324
- <i>A will-o'-the-wisp</i>
- <i>A clown</i>

71
00:12:08,994 --> 00:12:12,350
<i>Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her</i>

72
00:12:12,998 --> 00:12:16,354
<i>Many a thing she ought to understand</i>

73
00:12:16,836 --> 00:12:20,533
<i>But how do you make her stay
And listen to all you say?</i>

74
00:12:21,207 --> 00:12:24,563
<i>How do you keep a wave
Upon the sand?</i>

75
00:12:24,944 --> 00:12:28,869
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

76
00:12:29,415 --> 00:12:34,614
<i>How do you hold a moonbeam</i>

77
00:12:35,187 --> 00:12:40,614
<i>In your hand?</i>

78
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:45,219
<i>When I'm with her I'm confused
Out of focus and bemused</i>

79
00:12:45,464 --> 00:12:48,922
<i>And I never know exactly where I am</i>

80
00:12:49,135 --> 00:12:52,468
- <i>Unpredictable as weather</i>
- <i>She's as flighty as a feather</i>

81
00:12:52,838 --> 00:12:54,635
- <i>She's a darling</i>
- <i>She's a demon</i>

82
00:12:54,874 --> 00:12:56,239
<i>She's a lamb</i>

83
00:12:56,609 --> 00:13:00,238
<i>She'll out pester any pest
Drive a hornet from its nest</i>

84
00:13:00,479 --> 00:13:03,778
<i>She can throw a whirling dervish
Out of whirl</i>

85
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:07,908
- <i>She is gentle, she is wild</i>
- <i>She's a riddle, she's a child</i>

86
00:13:08,454 --> 00:13:11,048
- <i>She's a headache</i>
- <i>She's an angel</i>

87
00:13:11,257 --> 00:13:15,114
<i>She's a girl</i>

88
00:13:15,928 --> 00:13:19,557
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

89
00:13:19,999 --> 00:13:23,662
<i>How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?</i>

90
00:13:24,003 --> 00:13:27,564
<i>How do you find a word
That means Maria?</i>

91
00:13:27,807 --> 00:13:29,798
- <i>A flibbertigibbet</i>
- <i>A will-o'-the-wisp</i>

92
00:13:30,009 --> 00:13:31,670
<i>A clown</i>

93
00:13:32,278 --> 00:13:35,736
<i>Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her</i>

94
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:39,615
<i>Many a thing she ought to understand</i>

95
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:44,085
- <i>But how do you make her stay?</i>
- <i>And listen to all you say?</i>

96
00:13:44,456 --> 00:13:48,244
<i>How do you keep a wave
Upon the sand?</i>

97
00:13:48,761 --> 00:13:54,119
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

98
00:14:10,516 --> 00:14:17,206
<i>How do you hold a moonbeam</i>

99
00:14:18,290 --> 00:14:24,616
<i>In your hand?</i>

100
00:14:36,475 --> 00:14:38,466
You may go in now, Maria.

101
00:14:51,056 --> 00:14:52,683
Come here, my child.

102
00:14:59,198 --> 00:15:00,563
Now sit down.

103
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:05,061
Reverend Mother, I'm sorry.
I couldn't help myself.

104
00:15:05,304 --> 00:15:08,228
- The hills were beckoning and before--
- Dear.

105
00:15:08,707 --> 00:15:10,629
I haven't summoned you for apologies.

106
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:13,105
Please let me ask for forgiveness.

107
00:15:13,779 --> 00:15:15,041
If you'll feel better.

108
00:15:15,948 --> 00:15:18,314
Yes, you see,
the sky was so blue today...

109
00:15:18,584 --> 00:15:22,372
...and everything was so green and
fragrant, I had to be a part of it.

110
00:15:22,621 --> 00:15:27,081
The Untersberg led me higher like
it wanted me to go through the clouds.

111
00:15:27,293 --> 00:15:29,420
Suppose darkness had come
and you were lost?

112
00:15:29,628 --> 00:15:31,892
Mother, I could never be lost
up there.

113
00:15:32,131 --> 00:15:34,964
That's my mountain.
I was brought up on it.

114
00:15:35,167 --> 00:15:37,465
It was the mountain that led me
to you.

115
00:15:38,270 --> 00:15:41,228
When I was a child,
I would come down and climb a tree...

116
00:15:41,473 --> 00:15:43,270
...and look in your garden.

117
00:15:43,475 --> 00:15:46,433
I'd see the sisters at work
and hear them sing.

118
00:15:47,780 --> 00:15:51,409
Which brings me to another
transgression, Reverend Mother.

119
00:15:51,617 --> 00:15:53,778
I was singing out there today.

120
00:15:54,420 --> 00:15:58,447
Only in the abbey do we have rules
about postulants singing.

121
00:15:58,657 --> 00:16:00,648
I can't stop wherever I am.

122
00:16:00,926 --> 00:16:03,258
Worse, I can't seem to stop
saying things.

123
00:16:03,495 --> 00:16:05,759
Everything I think and feel.

124
00:16:05,998 --> 00:16:07,488
Some call that "honesty."

125
00:16:07,666 --> 00:16:10,055
Oh, but it's terrible,
Reverend Mother!

126
00:16:10,302 --> 00:16:14,159
You know how Sister Berthe makes me
kiss the floor after a disagreement?

127
00:16:14,573 --> 00:16:18,065
Lately, I kiss the floor when I see
her coming, just to save time.

128
00:16:20,713 --> 00:16:21,873
Maria...

129
00:16:22,881 --> 00:16:25,873
...when you saw us over the wall
and longed to be with us...

130
00:16:26,151 --> 00:16:30,850
...that didn't mean you were prepared
for the way we live here, did it?

131
00:16:32,191 --> 00:16:34,614
No, Mother, but I pray and I try.

132
00:16:34,827 --> 00:16:36,522
And I am learning. I really am.

133
00:16:36,795 --> 00:16:39,457
What is the most important lesson
you have learned here?

134
00:16:40,132 --> 00:16:43,898
To find out what is the will of God
and do it wholeheartedly.

135
00:16:46,739 --> 00:16:47,865
Maria...

136
00:16:49,375 --> 00:16:52,173
...it seems to be God's will
that you leave us.

137
00:16:52,411 --> 00:16:53,901
- Leave?
- Only for a while.

138
00:16:54,413 --> 00:16:56,745
No, Mother!
Please don't send me away!

139
00:16:57,016 --> 00:17:01,248
This is where I belong. It's my home,
my family. It's my life.

140
00:17:01,920 --> 00:17:04,912
- Are you truly ready for it?
- Yes, I am.

141
00:17:05,157 --> 00:17:10,049
If you go out into the world for a time,
knowing what we expect of you...

142
00:17:10,329 --> 00:17:13,059
...you will find out
if you can expect it of yourself.

143
00:17:13,265 --> 00:17:17,554
I know what you expect, Mother,
and I can do it! I promise I can!

144
00:17:21,140 --> 00:17:22,368
Yes, Mother.

145
00:17:24,443 --> 00:17:26,138
If it is God's will.

146
00:17:28,380 --> 00:17:33,443
There is a family near Salzburg that
needs a governess until September.

147
00:17:33,719 --> 00:17:35,914
- September?
- For seven children.

148
00:17:36,555 --> 00:17:37,579
Seven children?!

149
00:17:37,856 --> 00:17:39,084
Do you like children?

150
00:17:39,892 --> 00:17:41,689
Well, yes, but seven!

151
00:17:42,861 --> 00:17:46,024
I will tell Captain von Trapp
to expect you tomorrow.

152
00:17:46,565 --> 00:17:47,896
Captain?

153
00:17:48,667 --> 00:17:53,457
A retired officer of the Imperial Navy.
A fine man and a brave one.

154
00:17:53,739 --> 00:17:56,435
His wife died,
and he is alone with the children.

155
00:17:56,675 --> 00:18:00,941
I understand he has had a difficult
time keeping a governess there.

156
00:18:01,747 --> 00:18:04,045
Why difficult, Reverend Mother?

157
00:18:05,417 --> 00:18:08,306
The Lord will show you
in his own good time.

158
00:18:45,157 --> 00:18:47,648
When the Lord closes a door...

159
00:18:47,860 --> 00:18:50,351
...somewhere he opens a window.

160
00:18:52,764 --> 00:18:56,530
<i>What will this day be like?</i>

161
00:18:57,970 --> 00:18:59,801
<i>I wonder</i>

162
00:19:06,678 --> 00:19:10,603
<i>What will my future be?</i>

163
00:19:11,650 --> 00:19:13,777
<i>I wonder</i>

164
00:19:15,554 --> 00:19:18,318
<i>It could be so exciting</i>

165
00:19:18,757 --> 00:19:21,749
<i>To be out in the world
To be free</i>

166
00:19:22,060 --> 00:19:25,154
<i>My heart should be wildly rejoicing</i>

167
00:19:26,331 --> 00:19:31,462
<i>Oh, what's the matter with me?</i>

168
00:19:32,004 --> 00:19:35,030
<i>I've always longed for adventure</i>

169
00:19:35,307 --> 00:19:38,868
<i>To do the things I've never dared</i>

170
00:19:39,144 --> 00:19:42,272
<i>Now here I'm facing adventure</i>

171
00:19:42,714 --> 00:19:48,402
<i>Then why am I so scared?</i>

172
00:19:52,224 --> 00:19:54,488
<i>A captain with seven children</i>

173
00:19:55,427 --> 00:19:57,486
<i>What's so fearsome about that?</i>

174
00:20:00,699 --> 00:20:03,224
<i>I must stop these doubts
All these worries</i>

175
00:20:03,535 --> 00:20:06,197
<i>If I don't, I just know I'll turn back</i>

176
00:20:06,672 --> 00:20:09,561
<i>I must dream of the things
I am seeking</i>

177
00:20:11,109 --> 00:20:15,705
<i>I am seeking the courage I lack</i>

178
00:20:16,848 --> 00:20:20,079
<i>The courage to serve them
With reliance</i>

179
00:20:20,919 --> 00:20:23,581
<i>Face my mistakes without defiance</i>

180
00:20:24,089 --> 00:20:25,818
<i>Show them I'm worthy</i>

181
00:20:26,058 --> 00:20:28,447
<i>And while I show them</i>

182
00:20:28,961 --> 00:20:32,749
<i>I'll show me</i>

183
00:20:32,965 --> 00:20:38,221
<i>So let them bring on
All their problems</i>

184
00:20:38,604 --> 00:20:41,596
<i>I'll do better than my best</i>

185
00:20:42,207 --> 00:20:45,096
<i>I have confidence
They'll put me to the test</i>

186
00:20:45,544 --> 00:20:48,638
<i>But I'll make them see
I have confidence in me</i>

187
00:20:49,114 --> 00:20:52,140
<i>Somehow, I will impress them</i>

188
00:20:52,651 --> 00:20:55,882
<i>I will be firm but kind</i>

189
00:20:56,221 --> 00:20:59,452
<i>And all those children
Heaven bless them</i>

190
00:20:59,725 --> 00:21:02,990
<i>They will look up to me
And mind me</i>

191
00:21:03,262 --> 00:21:06,390
<i>With each step, I am more certain</i>

192
00:21:06,632 --> 00:21:09,726
<i>Everything will turn out fine</i>

193
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:13,128
<i>I have confidence
The world can all be mine</i>

194
00:21:13,438 --> 00:21:18,637
<i>They'll have to agree
I have confidence in me</i>

195
00:21:20,479 --> 00:21:23,243
<i>I have confidence in sunshine</i>

196
00:21:23,482 --> 00:21:26,406
<i>I have confidence in rain</i>

197
00:21:26,785 --> 00:21:29,674
<i>I have confidence
That spring will come again</i>

198
00:21:29,955 --> 00:21:33,015
<i>Besides which you see
I have confidence in me</i>

199
00:21:33,458 --> 00:21:36,313
<i>Strength doesn't lie in numbers</i>

200
00:21:36,662 --> 00:21:39,586
<i>Strength doesn't lie in wealth</i>

201
00:21:39,965 --> 00:21:43,264
<i>Strength lies in nights
Of peaceful slumbers</i>

202
00:21:43,502 --> 00:21:46,426
<i>When you wake up, wake up
It's healthy</i>

203
00:21:46,672 --> 00:21:49,436
<i>All I trust I leave my heart to</i>

204
00:21:49,941 --> 00:21:52,671
<i>All I trust becomes my own</i>

205
00:21:53,045 --> 00:21:57,311
<i>I have confidence in confidence alone</i>

206
00:22:12,497 --> 00:22:14,124
Oh, help.

207
00:22:26,311 --> 00:22:32,739
<i>I have confidence in confidence alone</i>

208
00:22:33,719 --> 00:22:38,543
<i>Besides which you see
I have confidence</i>

209
00:22:38,824 --> 00:22:45,047
<i>In me</i>

210
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:54,570
Hello. Here I am.

211
00:22:57,075 --> 00:22:59,236
I'm from the convent.
I'm the new governess, captain.

212
00:23:00,912 --> 00:23:04,177
And I'm the old butler, fräulein.

213
00:23:06,084 --> 00:23:07,915
Well, how do you do?

214
00:23:18,430 --> 00:23:22,526
You'll wait here, please.

215
00:24:48,854 --> 00:24:52,984
In the future, remember certain rooms
in this house are not to be disturbed.

216
00:24:54,125 --> 00:24:55,615
Yes, captain, sir.

217
00:25:03,502 --> 00:25:08,735
- Why do you stare at me that way?
- You don't look like a sea captain.

218
00:25:10,008 --> 00:25:13,034
I'm afraid you don't look
very much like a governess.

219
00:25:13,612 --> 00:25:14,840
- Turn around.
- What?

220
00:25:15,046 --> 00:25:16,377
Turn.

221
00:25:19,618 --> 00:25:20,880
Hat off.

222
00:25:23,989 --> 00:25:26,617
Put on another dress
before meeting the children.

223
00:25:26,858 --> 00:25:28,485
But I don't have another.

224
00:25:28,727 --> 00:25:31,616
When we enter the abbey,
our worldly clothes go to the poor.

225
00:25:31,863 --> 00:25:33,057
What about this one?

226
00:25:33,331 --> 00:25:34,662
The poor didn't want it.

227
00:25:36,501 --> 00:25:39,993
There wasn't time to make a new dress.
I can make clothes.

228
00:25:41,239 --> 00:25:43,503
I'll see that you get some material.

229
00:25:44,209 --> 00:25:45,767
Today, if possible.

230
00:25:46,778 --> 00:25:48,541
- Now, fräulein...
- Maria.

231
00:25:48,780 --> 00:25:50,736
I don't know how much
the abbess told you.

232
00:25:50,916 --> 00:25:54,340
- Not much.
- You are the twelfth governess...

233
00:25:54,553 --> 00:25:57,044
...to look after my children
since their mother died.

234
00:25:57,222 --> 00:25:59,417
I trust you will be an improvement
on the last one.

235
00:25:59,691 --> 00:26:01,522
She stayed only two hours.

236
00:26:03,228 --> 00:26:05,788
What's wrong with the children, sir?

237
00:26:07,265 --> 00:26:11,656
Nothing is wrong with the children,
only the governesses.

238
00:26:11,937 --> 00:26:16,863
They could not maintain discipline,
without which the house cannot be run.

239
00:26:17,776 --> 00:26:19,607
Drill them in their studies.

240
00:26:19,878 --> 00:26:23,370
I will not permit them to dream
away their summer holidays.

241
00:26:23,615 --> 00:26:26,277
Each afternoon,
they march, breathing deeply.

242
00:26:26,551 --> 00:26:28,143
Bedtime is to be strictly observed.

243
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:29,378
When do they play?

244
00:26:29,588 --> 00:26:33,615
You will see to it that they conduct
themselves with the utmost decorum.

245
00:26:33,892 --> 00:26:36,816
- I am placing you in command.
- Yes, sir.

246
00:27:57,475 --> 00:27:58,635
Now...

247
00:27:59,210 --> 00:28:02,168
...this is your new governess,
Fräulein Maria.

248
00:28:03,848 --> 00:28:05,839
Give your name at your signal.

249
00:28:06,051 --> 00:28:10,215
Fräulein, listen carefully. Learn
their signals so you can call them.

250
00:28:11,523 --> 00:28:12,922
Liesl.

251
00:28:13,191 --> 00:28:14,920
Friedrich.

252
00:28:15,193 --> 00:28:16,717
Louisa.

253
00:28:16,995 --> 00:28:18,292
Kurt.

254
00:28:18,496 --> 00:28:19,520
Brigitta.

255
00:28:19,798 --> 00:28:21,060
Marta.

256
00:28:27,439 --> 00:28:28,804
Gretl.

257
00:28:33,411 --> 00:28:36,835
Now, let's see how well you listened.

258
00:28:37,082 --> 00:28:39,448
I won't need to whistle for them,
Reverend Captain.

259
00:28:39,718 --> 00:28:43,176
I mean, I'll use their names.
Such lovely names.

260
00:28:43,388 --> 00:28:46,551
Fräulein, this is a large house.
The grounds are extensive.

261
00:28:46,825 --> 00:28:49,555
And I will not have anyone shouting.

262
00:28:49,728 --> 00:28:51,559
You will take this, please.
Learn to use it.

263
00:28:51,730 --> 00:28:53,391
The children will help you.

264
00:28:55,433 --> 00:28:59,426
Now, when I want you,
this is what you will hear.

265
00:29:00,271 --> 00:29:02,102
Oh, no, sir. I'm sorry, sir!

266
00:29:02,974 --> 00:29:04,464
I could never answer to a whistle.

267
00:29:04,743 --> 00:29:07,371
Whistles are for animals,
not for children.

268
00:29:07,612 --> 00:29:09,637
And definitely not for me.

269
00:29:09,914 --> 00:29:12,576
It would be too humiliating.

270
00:29:13,384 --> 00:29:18,583
Fräulein, were you this much trouble
at the abbey?

271
00:29:18,890 --> 00:29:19,982
Oh, much more, sir.

272
00:29:31,102 --> 00:29:32,660
I don't know your signal.

273
00:29:34,139 --> 00:29:36,767
You may call me "captain."

274
00:29:49,687 --> 00:29:51,177
At ease.

275
00:29:53,958 --> 00:29:55,516
Now that there's just us...

276
00:29:55,760 --> 00:29:59,924
...would you please tell me all your
names again and how old you are.

277
00:30:00,431 --> 00:30:04,424
I'm Liesl. I'm 16 years old,
and I don't need a governess.

278
00:30:05,170 --> 00:30:08,264
I'm glad you told me, Liesl.
We'll just be good friends.

279
00:30:10,408 --> 00:30:14,196
I'm Friedrich. I'm 14.
I'm impossible.

280
00:30:14,479 --> 00:30:16,174
Really? Who told you that, Friedrich?

281
00:30:16,414 --> 00:30:19,941
Fräulein Josephine.
Four governesses ago.

282
00:30:20,351 --> 00:30:21,841
I'm Brigitta.

283
00:30:23,655 --> 00:30:27,648
You didn't tell me how old you are,
Louisa.

284
00:30:28,359 --> 00:30:30,623
I'm Brigitta. She's Louisa.

285
00:30:30,862 --> 00:30:33,626
She's 13 years old, and you're smart.

286
00:30:33,865 --> 00:30:37,631
I'm 10, and I think your dress
is the ugliest one I ever saw.

287
00:30:37,936 --> 00:30:40,530
- Brigitta, you shouldn't say that.
- Why not?

288
00:30:40,738 --> 00:30:43,036
- Don't you think it's ugly?
- Of course.

289
00:30:43,308 --> 00:30:46,004
But Fräulein Helga's was ugliest.

290
00:30:46,244 --> 00:30:48,872
I'm Kurt. I'm 11.
I'm incorrigible.

291
00:30:49,147 --> 00:30:52,241
- Congratulations.
- What's "incorrigible"?

292
00:30:52,517 --> 00:30:56,374
I think it means you want
to be treated like a boy.

293
00:30:58,556 --> 00:31:01,855
I'm Marta, and I'm going to be
7 on Tuesday.

294
00:31:02,093 --> 00:31:03,492
I'd like a pink parasol.

295
00:31:04,696 --> 00:31:06,220
Pink's my favorite color too.

296
00:31:08,566 --> 00:31:09,726
Yes, you're Gretl.

297
00:31:10,668 --> 00:31:12,397
And you're 5 years old?

298
00:31:12,837 --> 00:31:14,828
My, you're practically a lady.

299
00:31:17,342 --> 00:31:20,368
I have to tell you a secret.
I've never been a governess.

300
00:31:21,913 --> 00:31:24,711
You don't know anything
about being a governess?

301
00:31:24,983 --> 00:31:26,348
Nothing. I'll need lots of advice.

302
00:31:27,252 --> 00:31:31,780
The best way to start is to tell
Father to mind his own business.

303
00:31:32,056 --> 00:31:33,853
Never come to dinner on time.

304
00:31:34,058 --> 00:31:36,356
Never eat your soup quietly.

305
00:31:37,061 --> 00:31:39,086
During dessert,
always blow your nose.

306
00:31:39,364 --> 00:31:42,094
Don't you believe a word they say,
Fräulein Maria.

307
00:31:42,367 --> 00:31:45,723
- Oh, why not?
- Because I like you.

308
00:31:46,537 --> 00:31:48,493
Children, outside for your walk.

309
00:31:48,740 --> 00:31:50,571
Father's orders. Hurry up.

310
00:31:50,808 --> 00:31:52,105
Quick, quick, quick.

311
00:31:52,377 --> 00:31:55,574
Fräulein Maria, I'm Frau Schmidt,
the housekeeper.

312
00:31:55,813 --> 00:31:56,905
How do you do.

313
00:31:57,081 --> 00:31:59,914
I'll show you to your room.
Follow me.

314
00:32:11,062 --> 00:32:12,791
Poor little dears.

315
00:32:25,543 --> 00:32:29,832
You're very lucky.
With Fräulein Helga it was a snake.

316
00:32:43,795 --> 00:32:45,092
Good evening.

317
00:32:46,497 --> 00:32:50,092
- Good evening, children.
- Good evening, Fräulein Maria.

318
00:32:57,275 --> 00:32:58,936
Enchanting little ritual.

319
00:32:59,143 --> 00:33:01,839
Something you learned at the abbey?

320
00:33:03,081 --> 00:33:05,345
No.

321
00:33:07,018 --> 00:33:08,315
Rheumatism.

322
00:33:18,096 --> 00:33:21,224
Excuse me, captain.
Haven't we forgotten to thank the Lord?

323
00:33:29,474 --> 00:33:32,466
For what we receive,
may the Lord make us truly thankful.

324
00:33:33,011 --> 00:33:34,899
- Amen.
- Amen.

325
00:33:39,484 --> 00:33:41,372
I'd like to thank you all...

326
00:33:41,619 --> 00:33:44,611
...for the precious gift
you left in my pocket today.

327
00:33:48,059 --> 00:33:49,890
What gift?

328
00:33:53,031 --> 00:33:55,192
It's a secret between
the children and me.

329
00:33:55,400 --> 00:33:59,063
Then I suggest you keep it,
and let us eat.

330
00:33:59,437 --> 00:34:01,393
Knowing how nervous
I must have been...

331
00:34:01,672 --> 00:34:04,061
...a stranger in a new household...

332
00:34:04,275 --> 00:34:07,369
...knowing how important it was
for me to feel accepted...

333
00:34:07,645 --> 00:34:11,843
...it was so kind and thoughtful of
you to make my first moments here...

334
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:14,245
...so warm and happy...

335
00:34:14,519 --> 00:34:16,248
...and pleasant.

336
00:34:25,530 --> 00:34:27,555
- What is the matter, Marta?
- Nothing.

337
00:34:39,944 --> 00:34:40,968
Fräulein...

338
00:34:41,245 --> 00:34:45,067
...is it to be at every meal
or merely at dinnertime...

339
00:34:45,283 --> 00:34:49,879
...that you intend leading us through
this rare and wonderful new world...

340
00:34:50,088 --> 00:34:51,749
...of indigestion?

341
00:34:53,291 --> 00:34:56,124
They're all right, captain.
They're just happy.

342
00:35:14,912 --> 00:35:17,608
- Rolfe, good evening.
- Good evening, Franz.

343
00:35:17,849 --> 00:35:20,613
- I trust everything is under control?
- Yes, yes.

344
00:35:22,220 --> 00:35:24,643
- Are there any developments?
- Perhaps.

345
00:35:24,856 --> 00:35:27,017
- Is the captain home?
- He's at dinner.

346
00:35:27,291 --> 00:35:29,623
- With the family?
- Yes.

347
00:35:29,861 --> 00:35:31,624
Give him this telegram at once.

348
00:35:32,430 --> 00:35:33,454
Certainly.

349
00:35:45,143 --> 00:35:46,872
A telegram for you, sir.

350
00:35:49,747 --> 00:35:51,544
Franz? Who delivered it?

351
00:35:51,849 --> 00:35:53,874
That young lad Rolfe, of course.

352
00:35:56,154 --> 00:35:57,883
Father, may I be excused?

353
00:35:58,856 --> 00:36:03,316
Children, in the morning
I shall be going to Vienna.

354
00:36:03,628 --> 00:36:06,051
Not again, Father!

355
00:36:09,967 --> 00:36:11,992
How long will you be gone this time?

356
00:36:12,770 --> 00:36:14,169
I'm not sure, Gretl.

357
00:36:14,405 --> 00:36:18,000
- To visit Baroness Schraeder again?
- Mind your own business!

358
00:36:18,976 --> 00:36:20,864
As a matter of fact, yes, Louisa.

359
00:36:22,680 --> 00:36:26,502
- Why can't we ever see the baroness?
- Why would she want to see you?

360
00:36:26,784 --> 00:36:31,676
You are going to see the baroness.
I'm bringing her back with me to visit.

361
00:36:33,191 --> 00:36:34,920
And Uncle Max.

362
00:36:35,193 --> 00:36:37,684
Uncle Max!

363
00:36:53,711 --> 00:36:55,008
Rolfe!

364
00:36:58,082 --> 00:36:59,106
Oh, Rolfe!

365
00:37:01,719 --> 00:37:04,608
- No, Liesl. We mustn't!
- Why not, silly?

366
00:37:04,889 --> 00:37:07,517
- I don't know--
- Isn't this why you're waiting?

367
00:37:07,758 --> 00:37:09,589
Yes, of course.

368
00:37:09,860 --> 00:37:12,624
- I've missed you, Liesl.
- You have? How much?

369
00:37:12,897 --> 00:37:16,719
I even thought of sending a telegram,
so I'd be able to deliver it here.

370
00:37:16,968 --> 00:37:20,859
Oh, that's a lovely thought!
Why don't you, right now?

371
00:37:21,105 --> 00:37:25,269
- But I'm here!
- Please, Rolfe. Send me a telegram.

372
00:37:25,543 --> 00:37:28,967
I'll start it for you.
"Dear Liesl..."

373
00:37:29,647 --> 00:37:32,707
"Dear Liesl: I'd like to be able
to tell you...

374
00:37:32,883 --> 00:37:35,716
...how I feel about you. Stop.

375
00:37:35,953 --> 00:37:40,481
Unfortunately, this wire
is already too expensive.

376
00:37:40,725 --> 00:37:42,124
Sincerely, Rolfe."

377
00:37:42,360 --> 00:37:45,090
- "Sincerely"?
- Cordially.

378
00:37:45,296 --> 00:37:47,958
- "Cordially"?
- Affectionately?

379
00:37:50,301 --> 00:37:52,360
Will there be any reply?

380
00:37:53,638 --> 00:37:55,799
"Dear Rolfe: Stop.

381
00:37:56,807 --> 00:37:59,935
Don't stop! Your Liesl."

382
00:38:01,612 --> 00:38:05,469
If only we didn't have to wait
for someone to send Father a telegram.

383
00:38:05,750 --> 00:38:08,139
How do I know when I'll see you again?

384
00:38:09,020 --> 00:38:10,282
Well, let's see...

385
00:38:13,291 --> 00:38:15,179
I could come here by mistake.

386
00:38:16,193 --> 00:38:20,892
With a telegram for Colonel Schneider!
He's here from Berlin staying with--

387
00:38:21,799 --> 00:38:25,098
No one knows he's here.
Don't tell your father.

388
00:38:25,336 --> 00:38:28,499
- Why not?
- Your father's so Austrian.

389
00:38:28,706 --> 00:38:30,003
We're all Austrian.

390
00:38:30,207 --> 00:38:34,632
Some think we ought to be German, and
they're very mad at those who don't.

391
00:38:34,845 --> 00:38:36,642
They're getting ready to--

392
00:38:38,316 --> 00:38:40,705
Let's hope your father
doesn't get into trouble.

393
00:38:40,985 --> 00:38:45,945
Don't worry. He's a big naval hero.
He was even decorated by the emperor.

394
00:38:46,157 --> 00:38:49,422
I don't worry about him.
I worry about his daughter.

395
00:38:49,960 --> 00:38:52,326
- Me? Why?
- Well, you're so--

396
00:38:54,498 --> 00:38:58,525
- You're such a baby!
- I'm 16. What's such a baby about that?

397
00:39:00,805 --> 00:39:04,138
<i>You wait, little girl
On an empty stage</i>

398
00:39:04,542 --> 00:39:07,375
<i>For fate to turn the light on</i>

399
00:39:08,546 --> 00:39:11,743
<i>Your life, little girl
Is an empty page</i>

400
00:39:12,049 --> 00:39:15,382
<i>That men will want to write on</i>

401
00:39:16,854 --> 00:39:22,087
<i>To write on</i>

402
00:39:23,260 --> 00:39:27,185
<i>You are 16 going on 17</i>

403
00:39:27,398 --> 00:39:30,890
<i>Baby, it's time to think</i>

404
00:39:31,402 --> 00:39:35,065
<i>Better beware
Be canny and careful</i>

405
00:39:35,339 --> 00:39:38,729
<i>Baby, you're on the brink</i>

406
00:39:39,243 --> 00:39:43,031
<i>You are 16 going on 17</i>

407
00:39:43,347 --> 00:39:46,771
<i>Fellows will fall in line</i>

408
00:39:47,251 --> 00:39:50,607
<i>Eager young lads
And roués and cads</i>

409
00:39:50,855 --> 00:39:54,677
<i>Will offer you food and wine</i>

410
00:39:55,226 --> 00:39:58,559
<i>Totally unprepared are you</i>

411
00:39:59,096 --> 00:40:02,554
<i>To face a world of men</i>

412
00:40:03,267 --> 00:40:07,033
<i>Timid and shy and scared are you</i>

413
00:40:07,204 --> 00:40:11,129
<i>Of things beyond your ken</i>

414
00:40:11,542 --> 00:40:15,399
<i>You need someone older and wiser</i>

415
00:40:15,613 --> 00:40:19,401
<i>Telling you what to do</i>

416
00:40:19,717 --> 00:40:23,141
<i>I am 17 going on 18</i>

417
00:40:23,421 --> 00:40:29,382
<i>I'll take care of you</i>

418
00:41:01,826 --> 00:41:05,250
<i>I am 16 going on 17</i>

419
00:41:05,463 --> 00:41:08,626
<i>I know that I'm naive</i>

420
00:41:09,266 --> 00:41:12,326
<i>Fellows I meet
May tell me I'm sweet</i>

421
00:41:12,570 --> 00:41:16,062
<i>And willingly I believe</i>

422
00:41:16,674 --> 00:41:20,007
<i>I am 16 going on 17</i>

423
00:41:20,444 --> 00:41:23,607
<i>Innocent as a rose</i>

424
00:41:24,081 --> 00:41:27,573
<i>Bachelor dandies
Drinkers of brandies</i>

425
00:41:27,818 --> 00:41:31,015
<i>What do I know of those?</i>

426
00:41:31,489 --> 00:41:34,788
<i>Totally unprepared am I</i>

427
00:41:35,092 --> 00:41:37,890
<i>To face a world of men</i>

428
00:41:39,029 --> 00:41:42,226
<i>Timid and shy and scared am I</i>

429
00:41:42,666 --> 00:41:46,022
<i>Of things beyond my ken</i>

430
00:41:46,837 --> 00:41:50,398
<i>I need someone older and wiser</i>

431
00:41:50,674 --> 00:41:53,837
<i>Telling me what to do</i>

432
00:41:54,411 --> 00:41:58,006
<i>You are 17 going on 18</i>

433
00:41:58,215 --> 00:42:03,539
<i>I'll depend on you</i>

434
00:43:56,967 --> 00:43:58,332
Come in.

435
00:43:59,370 --> 00:44:01,031
Frau Schmidt.

436
00:44:03,340 --> 00:44:05,137
For your new dresses.

437
00:44:05,376 --> 00:44:09,437
- The captain had these sent from town.
- Oh, how lovely!

438
00:44:09,680 --> 00:44:13,138
These will make the prettiest
clothes I've ever had.

439
00:44:13,384 --> 00:44:16,876
Do you think he would
get me more material if I asked?

440
00:44:17,154 --> 00:44:20,783
- How many dresses do you need?
- Not for me, for the children.

441
00:44:21,025 --> 00:44:23,118
I want to make them
some play clothes.

442
00:44:23,327 --> 00:44:26,888
The von Trapp children don't play.
They march.

443
00:44:27,364 --> 00:44:29,855
Surely you don't approve of that.

444
00:44:30,834 --> 00:44:33,200
Ever since the captain
lost his poor wife...

445
00:44:33,470 --> 00:44:36,166
...he runs this house as if on
one of his ships.

446
00:44:37,007 --> 00:44:38,372
Whistles, orders.

447
00:44:38,642 --> 00:44:40,507
No more music, no more laughing.

448
00:44:40,778 --> 00:44:44,270
Nothing that reminds him of her.
Even the children.

449
00:44:44,815 --> 00:44:45,873
But that's so wrong.

450
00:44:46,717 --> 00:44:48,207
Oh, well.

451
00:44:48,485 --> 00:44:52,148
How do you like your room?
There'll be new drapes at the windows.

452
00:44:52,389 --> 00:44:53,651
But these are fine.

453
00:44:53,891 --> 00:44:55,518
New ones have been ordered.

454
00:44:55,726 --> 00:44:59,059
- But I really don't need them.
- Good night, now.

455
00:44:59,329 --> 00:45:03,356
Frau Schmidt, if I asked the captain
tomorrow about the material...?

456
00:45:03,600 --> 00:45:08,025
- He's leaving in the morning.
- Of course. How long will he be gone?

457
00:45:08,672 --> 00:45:13,234
It depends. The last time he visited
the baroness, he stayed for a month.

458
00:45:14,411 --> 00:45:19,007
I shouldn't be saying this to you.
I don't know you that well.

459
00:45:19,249 --> 00:45:22,173
But if you ask me,
the captain's thinking seriously...

460
00:45:22,386 --> 00:45:24,616
...of marrying her before
summer's over.

461
00:45:24,855 --> 00:45:28,086
Wonderful! The children will
have a mother again.

462
00:45:29,560 --> 00:45:30,857
Yes.

463
00:45:31,095 --> 00:45:32,858
Well, good night.

464
00:45:33,063 --> 00:45:34,462
Good night.

465
00:45:52,850 --> 00:45:55,705
Dear Father, now I know
why you sent me here.

466
00:45:55,919 --> 00:45:58,774
To help these children
prepare for a new mother.

467
00:45:59,056 --> 00:46:02,355
And I pray this will become
a happy family in thy sight.

468
00:46:02,559 --> 00:46:05,653
God bless the captain.
God bless Liesl and Friedrich.

469
00:46:05,896 --> 00:46:10,060
God bless Louisa, Brigitta,
Marta and little Gretl.

470
00:46:10,367 --> 00:46:13,165
And I forgot the other boy.
What's his name?

471
