01:27:18,766 --> 01:27:22,463
Anytime you say the word, Georg,
you can be part of my new act:

1047
01:27:22,704 --> 01:27:25,195
The von Trapp Family Singers.

1048
01:27:26,274 --> 01:27:28,765
I have a wonderful idea, Georg.

1049
01:27:29,043 --> 01:27:31,466
Let's really fill this house
with music.

1050
01:27:31,746 --> 01:27:34,704
You must give a grand
and glorious party for me.

1051
01:27:34,949 --> 01:27:37,645
- A party?
- Yes, Father, please!

1052
01:27:37,885 --> 01:27:40,251
It's high time
I met all your friends...

1053
01:27:40,488 --> 01:27:43,048
...and they met me.
Don't you agree?

1054
01:27:43,291 --> 01:27:45,555
- I see what you mean.
- Oh, please!

1055
01:27:45,793 --> 01:27:48,956
Children, it's bedtime.
Come now, say good night.

1056
01:27:49,897 --> 01:27:51,159
Good night, Father.

1057
01:27:51,432 --> 01:27:54,230
- Good night.
- Good night, Baroness Schraeder.

1058
01:27:54,469 --> 01:27:56,061
Good night, Father.

1059
01:27:59,007 --> 01:28:00,872
Good night, Uncle Max.

1060
01:28:02,777 --> 01:28:05,940
It'll be my first party, Father!

1061
01:28:38,479 --> 01:28:41,107
- Captain.
- Herr Zeller. Baroness Schraeder.

1062
01:28:41,316 --> 01:28:44,444
- Good evening, Herr Zeller.
- Baroness.

1063
01:28:45,720 --> 01:28:48,211
How do you do? Good evening.

1064
01:29:08,843 --> 01:29:12,233
Did you notice the obvious
display of the Austrian flag?

1065
01:29:19,354 --> 01:29:21,151
The women look so beautiful.

1066
01:29:21,389 --> 01:29:22,686
I think they look ugly.

1067
01:29:23,024 --> 01:29:24,821
You're just scared of them.

1068
01:29:25,026 --> 01:29:27,324
Silly, only grown-up men fear women.

1069
01:29:27,895 --> 01:29:31,490
- I think the men look beautiful.
- How would you know?

1070
01:29:48,716 --> 01:29:50,741
Liesl, who are you dancing with?

1071
01:29:50,985 --> 01:29:52,612
Nobody.

1072
01:29:53,421 --> 01:29:55,343
Oh, yes, you are.

1073
01:29:57,792 --> 01:29:59,282
May I have this dance?

1074
01:29:59,527 --> 01:30:02,018
I'd be delighted, young man.

1075
01:30:08,736 --> 01:30:11,432
Why didn't you tell me
you could dance?

1076
01:30:11,706 --> 01:30:16,598
We feared you'd make us all dance.
The von Trapp Family Dancers.

1077
01:30:21,048 --> 01:30:22,743
What are they playing?

1078
01:30:22,950 --> 01:30:25,578
It's the Laendler.
An Austrian folk dance.

1079
01:30:25,753 --> 01:30:28,950
- Show me.
- I haven't danced since I was little.

1080
01:30:29,157 --> 01:30:31,113
You remember. Please?

1081
01:30:31,392 --> 01:30:33,314
- Well...
- Please.

1082
01:30:33,594 --> 01:30:35,789
All right. Come on over here.

1083
01:30:36,297 --> 01:30:39,130
Now you bow and I curtsy.

1084
01:30:40,067 --> 01:30:43,025
- Like this?
- Fine. Now we go for a little walk.

1085
01:30:43,271 --> 01:30:45,933
One, two, three. One, two, three.

1086
01:30:46,107 --> 01:30:50,806
One, two, three, step together.
Now, step hop, step hop.

1087
01:30:51,078 --> 01:30:53,740
Now turn under. Not quite.

1088
01:30:53,948 --> 01:30:57,907
This way. Hop step, hop.
And under.

1089
01:30:58,586 --> 01:31:00,281
Kurt, we'll have to practice.

1090
01:31:00,488 --> 01:31:01,978
Do allow me, will you?

1091
01:32:30,011 --> 01:32:32,172
I don't remember anymore.

1092
01:32:34,215 --> 01:32:36,547
- Your face is all red.
- Is it?

1093
01:32:37,852 --> 01:32:39,945
I don't suppose I'm used to dancing.

1094
01:32:42,690 --> 01:32:44,681
Why, that was beautifully done.

1095
01:32:44,892 --> 01:32:46,848
What a lovely couple you make.

1096
01:32:47,061 --> 01:32:49,188
It's time the children
said good night.

1097
01:32:49,430 --> 01:32:50,761
We'll be in the hall.

1098
01:32:51,032 --> 01:32:53,887
- We have something special prepared.
- Right!

1099
01:32:54,168 --> 01:32:55,362
Yes, come on!

1100
01:33:02,209 --> 01:33:04,541
All that needless worrying, Georg.

1101
01:33:04,779 --> 01:33:07,805
You thought you wouldn't find
a friend at the party.

1102
01:33:10,751 --> 01:33:14,278
- A bit chilly out tonight, isn't it?
- Oh, I don't know.

1103
01:33:14,555 --> 01:33:16,546
It seemed rather warm to me.

1104
01:33:20,895 --> 01:33:21,953
Ladies and gentlemen.

1105
01:33:22,730 --> 01:33:26,791
The children of Captain von Trapp
wish to say good night to you.

1106
01:33:41,082 --> 01:33:44,813
<i>There's a sad sort of clanging
From the clock in the hall</i>

1107
01:33:45,019 --> 01:33:48,648
<i>And the bells in the steeple too</i>

1108
01:33:49,223 --> 01:33:53,011
<i>And up in the nursery
An absurd little bird</i>

1109
01:33:53,294 --> 01:33:55,717
<i>Is popping out to say "coo-coo"</i>

1110
01:33:55,963 --> 01:33:57,362
<i>Coo-coo</i>

1111
01:33:57,865 --> 01:33:59,093
<i>Coo-coo</i>

1112
01:33:59,333 --> 01:34:01,494
- <i>Regretfully, they tell us</i>
- <i>Coo-coo</i>

1113
01:34:01,736 --> 01:34:03,101
- <i>But firmly they compel us</i>
- <i>Coo-coo</i>

1114
01:34:03,537 --> 01:34:06,370
- <i>To say goodbye</i>
- <i>Coo-coo</i>

1115
01:34:06,807 --> 01:34:11,938
<i>To you</i>

1116
01:34:15,349 --> 01:34:18,978
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, good night</i>

1117
01:34:19,453 --> 01:34:23,048
<i>I hate to go
And leave this pretty sight</i>

1118
01:34:30,331 --> 01:34:33,664
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, adieu</i>

1119
01:34:34,502 --> 01:34:37,858
<i>Adieu, adieu
To you and you and you</i>

1120
01:34:45,413 --> 01:34:49,008
<i>So long, farewell
Au revoir, auf Wiedersehen</i>

1121
01:34:49,316 --> 01:34:53,275
<i>I'd like to stay
And taste my first champagne</i>

1122
01:34:53,521 --> 01:34:55,910
- Yes?
- No.

1123
01:35:00,494 --> 01:35:03,884
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye</i>

1124
01:35:04,498 --> 01:35:08,229
<i>I leave and heave a sigh
And say goodbye</i>

1125
01:35:08,436 --> 01:35:12,429
<i>Goodbye</i>

1126
01:35:15,676 --> 01:35:18,565
<i>I'm glad to go</i>

1127
01:35:18,846 --> 01:35:21,679
<i>I cannot tell a lie</i>

1128
01:35:22,049 --> 01:35:24,711
<i>I flit, I float</i>

1129
01:35:25,519 --> 01:35:28,750
<i>I fleetly flee, I fly</i>

1130
01:35:38,833 --> 01:35:44,521
<i>The sun has gone to bed</i>

1131
01:35:44,772 --> 01:35:48,469
<i>And so must I</i>

1132
01:35:48,709 --> 01:35:51,098
<i>So long</i>

1133
01:35:51,378 --> 01:35:53,903
<i>Farewell</i>

1134
01:35:54,115 --> 01:35:59,542
<i>Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye</i>

1135
01:35:59,987 --> 01:36:05,084
<i>Goodbye</i>

1136
01:36:05,860 --> 01:36:11,116
<i>Goodbye</i>

1137
01:36:11,632 --> 01:36:17,855
<i>Goodbye</i>

1138
01:36:18,606 --> 01:36:26,103
<i>Goodbye</i>

1139
01:36:32,286 --> 01:36:35,016
Extraordinary!
What they'd do at the festival.

1140
01:36:35,289 --> 01:36:37,712
Young lady,
I must have a word with you.

1141
01:36:38,726 --> 01:36:42,787
Georg, you won't let this girl get away.
She must join the party.

1142
01:36:43,030 --> 01:36:45,453
- No, really I--
- Stop. Stop it now.

1143
01:36:45,699 --> 01:36:48,657
- Georg, please.
- You can if you want to, fräulein.

1144
01:36:48,869 --> 01:36:51,360
I insist.
You will be my dinner partner.

1145
01:36:51,572 --> 01:36:53,494
This is business. Franz...

1146
01:36:53,741 --> 01:36:56,938
...set another place next to mine
for Fräulein Maria.

1147
01:36:59,079 --> 01:37:01,843
- Whatever you say.
- It appears to be all arranged.

1148
01:37:02,583 --> 01:37:04,471
- It does.
- I'm not suitably dressed.

1149
01:37:05,553 --> 01:37:07,077
You can change. We'll wait.

1150
01:37:10,691 --> 01:37:13,546
Captain, you must be very proud
of your youngsters.

1151
01:37:13,727 --> 01:37:14,751
I am, thank you.

1152
01:37:14,962 --> 01:37:19,490
Is there a more beautiful expression
of what is good in our country...

1153
01:37:19,733 --> 01:37:23,191
...than the innocent voices
of our children?

1154
01:37:23,571 --> 01:37:24,970
Oh, come now, baron.

1155
01:37:25,206 --> 01:37:28,972
Would you have us believe that Austria
holds a monopoly on virtue?

1156
01:37:29,844 --> 01:37:33,974
Herr Zeller, some of us prefer
Austrian voices raised in song...

1157
01:37:34,215 --> 01:37:36,581
...to ugly German threats.

1158
01:37:37,685 --> 01:37:41,246
The ostrich buries his head
in the sand...

1159
01:37:41,522 --> 01:37:44,411
...and sometimes in the flag.

1160
01:37:44,992 --> 01:37:49,190
Perhaps those who would warn you that
the Anschluss is coming, and it is...

1161
01:37:49,430 --> 01:37:53,127
...would get further with you by setting
their words to music.

1162
01:37:53,367 --> 01:37:57,997
If the Nazis take over Austria, you
will be the entire trumpet section.

1163
01:37:58,305 --> 01:37:59,363
You flatter me.

1164
01:38:00,407 --> 01:38:04,264
Oh, how clumsy of me.
I meant to accuse you.

1165
01:38:12,052 --> 01:38:14,543
It's very kind of you
to offer to help me, baroness.

1166
01:38:14,755 --> 01:38:16,382
I'm delighted, Maria.

1167
01:38:16,790 --> 01:38:20,556
I really don't think I have anything
that would be appropriate.

1168
01:38:21,028 --> 01:38:25,124
Now where is that lovely little thing
you were wearing the other evening?

1169
01:38:25,399 --> 01:38:28,664
When the captain couldn't keep
his eyes off you.

1170
01:38:32,072 --> 01:38:33,903
Couldn't keep his eyes off me?

1171
01:38:35,175 --> 01:38:37,040
Come, my dear, we are women.

1172
01:38:37,278 --> 01:38:40,611
Let's not pretend we don't know
when a man notices us.

1173
01:38:40,848 --> 01:38:44,306
- Here we are.
- The captain notices everybody.

1174
01:38:44,852 --> 01:38:47,343
There's no need to feel
so defensive, Maria.

1175
01:38:47,588 --> 01:38:49,977
You are quite attractive, you know.

1176
01:38:50,257 --> 01:38:53,920
The captain would hardly be a man
if he didn't notice you.

1177
01:38:55,462 --> 01:38:57,851
Baroness, I hope you're joking.

1178
01:38:58,332 --> 01:38:59,594
Not at all.

1179
01:38:59,833 --> 01:39:01,425
I've never done a thing to--

1180
01:39:01,669 --> 01:39:03,296
You don't have to, my dear.

1181
01:39:03,938 --> 01:39:08,693
Nothing's more irresistible to a man
than a woman who's in love with him.

1182
01:39:09,977 --> 01:39:12,468
- In love with him?
- Of course.

1183
01:39:13,380 --> 01:39:16,804
What makes it so nice is
he thinks he's in love with you.

1184
01:39:19,520 --> 01:39:21,147
But that's not true.

1185
01:39:21,488 --> 01:39:25,015
Surely you've noticed the way
he looks into your eyes.

1186
01:39:25,292 --> 01:39:30,184
And you know, you blushed in his arms
when you were dancing just now.

1187
01:39:31,465 --> 01:39:33,160
Don't take it to heart.

1188
01:39:33,400 --> 01:39:35,698
He'll get over it soon enough,
I think.

1189
01:39:35,970 --> 01:39:37,892
Men do, you know.

1190
01:39:38,973 --> 01:39:39,997
Then I should go.

1191
01:39:41,342 --> 01:39:42,832
I mustn't stay here.

1192
01:39:53,320 --> 01:39:56,676
- Is there something I can do to help?
- No, nothing.

1193
01:39:58,525 --> 01:39:59,719
Yes.

1194
01:40:00,728 --> 01:40:02,753
Don't say a word to the captain.

1195
01:40:04,398 --> 01:40:07,925
No, I wouldn't dream of it.

1196
01:40:14,708 --> 01:40:16,335
Goodbye, Maria.

1197
01:40:17,144 --> 01:40:19,908
I'm sure you'll make a very fine nun.

1198
01:40:49,943 --> 01:40:51,934
Champagne, darling.

1199
01:40:52,379 --> 01:40:56,304
I feel like celebrating. Cheers.

1200
01:41:01,822 --> 01:41:04,711
- You know something.
- Perhaps.

1201
01:41:04,958 --> 01:41:09,486
If you're so clever, tell me how to
get fräulein to influence Georg.

1202
01:41:09,763 --> 01:41:12,391
I want those children in the festival.

1203
01:41:12,800 --> 01:41:15,098
Elsa, this is important to Austria.

1204
01:41:15,335 --> 01:41:17,064
Wouldn't do you any harm either.

1205
01:41:17,304 --> 01:41:18,828
I thought of that.

1206
01:41:19,106 --> 01:41:21,597
Well, if it's a matter of influence...

1207
01:41:21,775 --> 01:41:24,699
...maybe the one you have
to be talking to is me.

1208
01:44:51,118 --> 01:44:53,382
- Two.
- Three.

1209
01:44:53,620 --> 01:44:55,110
- Four.
- Five.

1210
01:44:56,390 --> 01:44:58,415
- Six.
- Seven.

1211
01:44:58,692 --> 01:45:00,250
Eight.

1212
01:45:00,560 --> 01:45:02,357
- Four.
- Two.

1213
01:45:03,497 --> 01:45:05,294
- Seven.
- Five.

1214
01:45:05,532 --> 01:45:07,762
- Two.
- Six.

1215
01:45:12,406 --> 01:45:14,431
Isn't this fun?

1216
01:45:15,776 --> 01:45:18,199
- Four.
- I'm number five.

1217
01:45:18,445 --> 01:45:20,606
- Oh, yes.
- Eight.

1218
01:45:20,881 --> 01:45:23,247
- Two.
- Four.

1219
01:45:23,650 --> 01:45:24,878
Six.

1220
01:45:27,387 --> 01:45:28,615
Two.

1221
01:45:29,756 --> 01:45:32,714
Baroness Schraeder, do you mind
if we stop now? We're tired.

1222
01:45:32,959 --> 01:45:34,915
Whatever you want, dear.

1223
01:45:35,162 --> 01:45:37,153
We'll do it again tomorrow.

1224
01:45:47,341 --> 01:45:49,536
The country's so restful, isn't it?

1225
01:45:50,577 --> 01:45:52,169
Have some lemonade.

1226
01:45:53,447 --> 01:45:54,846
There must be an easier way.

1227
01:45:56,249 --> 01:45:59,548
I get a fiendish delight thinking
of you as the mother of seven.

1228
01:46:00,487 --> 01:46:02,318
How do you plan to do it?

1229
01:46:02,589 --> 01:46:04,614
Darling, haven't you ever heard...

1230
01:46:04,858 --> 01:46:07,986
...of a delightful little thing
called boarding school?

1231
01:46:09,096 --> 01:46:11,360
Baroness Machiavelli.

1232
01:46:12,699 --> 01:46:14,690
Uncle Max, where's Father?

1233
01:46:14,968 --> 01:46:16,799
I think he's in the house.

1234
01:46:17,003 --> 01:46:19,563
What's the matter
with all you gloomy pussies?

1235
01:46:19,806 --> 01:46:22,502
- Nothing.
- I know. Let's have a rehearsal.

1236
01:46:22,676 --> 01:46:23,700
What for?

1237
01:46:23,877 --> 01:46:26,368
Let's make believe we're on-stage
at the festival.

1238
01:46:26,613 --> 01:46:30,470
- I don't feel like singing.
- Not without Fräulein Maria.

1239
01:46:30,717 --> 01:46:33,106
Liesl, get the guitar.
Come on, Marta.

1240
01:46:33,353 --> 01:46:36,311
Everybody into the group.
Get in your places.

1241
01:46:36,590 --> 01:46:39,320
Now be cheerful, right?
Give us the key, Liesl.

1242
01:46:41,228 --> 01:46:43,890
Now, impress me.

1243
01:46:47,901 --> 01:46:49,232
Gretl, why don't you sing?

1244
01:46:49,536 --> 01:46:54,496
- I can't. I've got a sore finger.
- But you sang so beautifully at the party.

1245
01:46:56,676 --> 01:47:00,339
Come on, all of you. Try something
you know. Enjoy it. Be cheerful.

1246
01:47:00,614 --> 01:47:02,206
All right, Liesl.

1247
01:47:04,184 --> 01:47:09,008
<i>The hills are alive</i>

1248
01:47:09,890 --> 01:47:17,080
<i>With the sound of music</i>

1249
01:47:18,698 --> 01:47:22,964
<i>With songs they have sung</i>

1250
01:47:24,004 --> 01:47:31,467
<i>For a thousand years</i>

1251
01:47:32,512 --> 01:47:37,609
<i>The hills fill my heart</i>

1252
01:47:38,185 --> 01:47:44,511
<i>With the sound of music</i>

1253
01:47:46,760 --> 01:47:48,853
They wanted to sing for me,
bless their hearts.

1254
01:47:49,129 --> 01:47:51,017
That's lovely, lovely.
Don't stop.

1255
01:47:55,035 --> 01:47:58,926
- Something long and cool, Georg?
- No, thank you, darling.

1256
01:47:59,372 --> 01:48:01,738
- Father?
- Yes, Brigitta?

1257
01:48:02,242 --> 01:48:04,506
Is it true Fräulein Maria
isn't coming back?

1258
01:48:04,778 --> 01:48:07,872
Yes, I suppose it's true.
What have we got here?

1259
01:48:08,215 --> 01:48:12,914
- Pink lemonade.
- Laced with lemonade.

1260
01:48:13,653 --> 01:48:15,143
I don't believe it, Father.

1261
01:48:16,556 --> 01:48:18,581
- What?
- About Fräulein Maria.

1262
01:48:18,959 --> 01:48:20,221
Oh, Fräulein Maria!

1263
01:48:20,460 --> 01:48:23,952
Didn't I tell you what her note said?
I'm sure I did.

1264
01:48:24,698 --> 01:48:27,223
She said she missed her life
at the abbey.

1265
01:48:27,467 --> 01:48:29,662
She had to leave us.

1266
01:48:29,870 --> 01:48:31,462
And that's all there is to it.

1267
01:48:33,206 --> 01:48:35,868
I think I'm brave enough to try
some of that.

1268
01:48:36,076 --> 01:48:38,806
- She didn't even say goodbye.
- She did in her note.

1269
01:48:39,079 --> 01:48:40,910
That isn't the same thing.

1270
01:48:41,181 --> 01:48:42,808
Not too sweet, not too sour.

1271
01:48:43,583 --> 01:48:45,574
Just too pink.

1272
01:48:46,987 --> 01:48:50,115
Father, who is our new governess
going to be?

1273
01:48:56,763 --> 01:48:57,787
Well...

1274
01:49:00,133 --> 01:49:05,423
...you're not going to have
a governess anymore.

1275
01:49:05,772 --> 01:49:08,400
- We're not?
- No.

1276
01:49:10,644 --> 01:49:12,771
You're going to have a new mother.

1277
01:49:13,847 --> 01:49:15,906
A new mother?

1278
01:49:16,716 --> 01:49:19,844
We talked about it last night.
It's all settled.

1279
01:49:20,086 --> 01:49:22,782
And we're all going to be very happy.

1280
01:49:55,789 --> 01:49:58,280
Well, all right, all right.
Run off and play.

1281
01:50:30,190 --> 01:50:31,214
Yes, my children?

1282
01:50:31,391 --> 01:50:33,780
- My name is Liesl.
- Yes, Liesl?

1283
01:50:34,294 --> 01:50:38,219
We, my brothers and sisters,
want to see Fräulein Maria.

1284
01:50:39,399 --> 01:50:41,390
Fräulein Maria?

1285
01:50:42,102 --> 01:50:44,093
Oh, Maria.

1286
01:50:46,039 --> 01:50:47,870
Come in, please.

1287
01:50:51,811 --> 01:50:53,301
Wait here.

1288
01:51:04,224 --> 01:51:07,421
I'm Sister Margaretta. I understand
you inquired about Maria.

1289
01:51:07,694 --> 01:51:10,185
We have to see her.
Will you tell her we're here?

1290
01:51:10,430 --> 01:51:13,024
- I'm afraid I can't do that.
- But you've got to!

1291
01:51:13,266 --> 01:51:15,359
- She's our governess.
- We want her back.

1292
01:51:15,568 --> 01:51:17,456
She didn't even say goodbye.

1293
01:51:17,737 --> 01:51:19,466
All we want to do is talk to her.

1294
01:51:20,273 --> 01:51:23,128
I'm very sorry,
but Maria is in seclusion.

1295
01:51:23,410 --> 01:51:26,470
- She hasn't been seeing anyone.
- She'll see us.

1296
01:51:26,746 --> 01:51:29,237
I want to show her my finger.

1297
01:51:29,449 --> 01:51:31,280
Some other time, dear.

1298
01:51:31,618 --> 01:51:32,915
I'll tell her you were here.

1299
01:51:33,153 --> 01:51:36,247
- It was sweet of you to call.
- We have to speak to her!

1300
01:51:36,890 --> 01:51:39,984
Run along, children.
Run along home.

1301
01:51:40,226 --> 01:51:41,887
I'm sure she'd like to see us.

1302
01:51:42,128 --> 01:51:44,392
Sister Margaretta, please.

1303
01:51:44,597 --> 01:51:48,363
- Goodbye, children.
- Sister Margaretta, may we, please?

1304
01:51:51,137 --> 01:51:52,866
What was that about, Sister?

1305
01:51:53,106 --> 01:51:55,267
The von Trapp children,
Reverend Mother.

1306
01:51:55,508 --> 01:51:57,999
They want to see Maria.

1307
01:51:58,244 --> 01:52:00,576
Has she spoken yet?
Has she told you anything?

1308
01:52:00,814 --> 01:52:04,807
She doesn't say a word,
Reverend Mother, except in prayer.

1309
01:52:05,085 --> 01:52:06,109
Poor child.

1310
01:52:06,286 --> 01:52:09,244
It's strange.
She seems happy to be back here...

1311
01:52:09,489 --> 01:52:12,754
...and yet she's unhappy too.

1312
01:52:13,993 --> 01:52:17,121
Perhaps I have been wrong
in leaving her alone so long.

1313
01:52:17,397 --> 01:52:20,025
Bring her to me,
even if she's not yet ready.

1314
01:52:20,266 --> 01:52:21,927
Yes, Reverend Mother.

1315
01:52:27,440 --> 01:52:30,967
Sister Augusta, take our new postulant
to the robing room.

1316
01:52:31,978 --> 01:52:34,208
God bless you, my daughter.

1317
01:52:40,453 --> 01:52:42,148
Yes, bring her in.

1318
01:52:51,197 --> 01:52:53,427
You've been unhappy. I'm sorry.

1319
01:52:55,468 --> 01:52:56,662
Reverend Mother.

1320
01:52:57,036 --> 01:52:59,664
Why did they send you back to us?

1321
01:53:00,507 --> 01:53:02,463
They didn't send me back. I left.

1322
01:53:04,978 --> 01:53:06,536
Sit down, Maria.

1323
01:53:07,046 --> 01:53:08,843
Tell me what happened.

1324
01:53:14,053 --> 01:53:15,350
I was frightened.

1325
01:53:15,588 --> 01:53:20,082
- Frightened? Were they unkind to you?
- Oh, no!

1326
01:53:20,360 --> 01:53:24,057
No, I was confused. I felt...

1327
01:53:25,532 --> 01:53:27,591
I've never felt that way before.

1328
01:53:27,867 --> 01:53:31,598
I couldn't stay. I knew that here
I'd be away from it. I'd be safe.

1329
01:53:31,871 --> 01:53:36,570
Maria, our abbey is not to be used
as an escape.

1330
01:53:36,843 --> 01:53:39,073
What is it you can't face?

1331
01:53:41,047 --> 01:53:42,480
I can't face him again.

1332
01:53:43,283 --> 01:53:44,773
Him?

1333
01:53:46,419 --> 01:53:48,478
Thank you, Sister Margaretta.

1334
01:53:58,064 --> 01:53:59,725
Captain von Trapp?

1335
01:54:05,138 --> 01:54:07,868
- Are you in love with him?
- I don't know!

1336
01:54:08,107 --> 01:54:09,540
I don't know. I--

1337
01:54:10,109 --> 01:54:13,931
The baroness said I was.
She said that he was in love with me.

1338
01:54:14,214 --> 01:54:16,808
But I didn't want to believe it.

1339
01:54:17,951 --> 01:54:20,215
There were times we looked
at each other.

1340
01:54:20,453 --> 01:54:22,011
I could hardly breathe.

1341
01:54:22,322 --> 01:54:25,086
- Did you let him see your feelings?
- I don't know.

1342
01:54:25,658 --> 01:54:28,320
That's what's torturing me.
I was on God's errand.

1343
01:54:28,561 --> 01:54:33,521
To have asked for his love would have
been wrong. I just couldn't stay.

1344
01:54:35,668 --> 01:54:38,523
I'm ready at this moment
to take my vows.

1345
01:54:39,405 --> 01:54:42,465
- Please help me.
- Maria.

1346
01:54:44,043 --> 01:54:48,742
The love of a man and a woman is holy.
You have a great capacity to love.

1347
01:54:48,982 --> 01:54:51,906
You must find out how God
wants you to spend your love.

1348
01:54:52,151 --> 01:54:56,042
But I pledged my life to God.
I pledged my life to his service.

1349
01:54:56,256 --> 01:55:00,613
My daughter, if you love this man,
it doesn't mean you love God less.

1350
01:55:02,295 --> 01:55:04,160
No.

1351
01:55:04,364 --> 01:55:06,252
You must find out.

1352
01:55:08,001 --> 01:55:10,492
You must go back.

1353
01:55:10,770 --> 01:55:13,625
You can't ask me to do that.
Please let me stay. I beg--

1354
01:55:15,942 --> 01:55:19,571
These walls were not built
to shut out problems.

1355
01:55:19,779 --> 01:55:21,337
You have to face them.

1356
01:55:21,948 --> 01:55:25,179
You have to live the life
you were born to live.

1357
01:55:31,057 --> 01:55:34,788
<i>Climb every mountain</i>

1358
01:55:35,628 --> 01:55:38,961
<i>Search high and low</i>

1359
01:55:39,999 --> 01:55:44,129
<i>Follow every byway</i>

1360
01:55:44,637 --> 01:55:48,801
<i>Every path you know</i>

1361
01:55:49,342 --> 01:55:53,438
<i>Climb every mountain</i>

1362
01:55:54,080 --> 01:55:57,868
<i>Ford every stream</i>

1363
01:55:58,651 --> 01:56:03,008
<i>Follow every rainbow</i>

1364
01:56:03,289 --> 01:56:07,111
<i>Till you find your dream</i>

1365
01:56:07,827 --> 01:56:10,887
<i>A dream that will need</i>

1366
01:56:11,164 --> 01:56:15,225
<i>All the love you can give</i>

1367
01:56:16,736 --> 01:56:19,796
<i>Every day of your life</i>

1368
01:56:20,406 --> 01:56:26,834
<i>For as long as you live</i>

1369
01:56:27,146 --> 01:56:31,310
<i>Climb every mountain</i>

1370
01:56:31,684 --> 01:56:36,007
<i>Ford every stream</i>

1371
01:56:36,255 --> 01:56:40,817
<i>Follow every rainbow</i>

1372
01:56:41,060 --> 01:56:49,422
<i>Till you find your dream</i>

1373
01:56:50,570 --> 01:56:54,062
<i>A dream that will need</i>

1374
01:56:54,340 --> 01:56:59,368
<i>All the love you can give</i>

1375
01:57:00,179 --> 01:57:03,444
<i>Every day of your life</i>

1376
01:57:03,883 --> 01:57:10,209
<i>For as long as you live</i>

1377
01:57:10,590 --> 01:57:14,856
<i>Climb every mountain</i>

1378
01:57:15,261 --> 01:57:19,186
<i>Ford every stream</i>

1379
01:57:19,866 --> 01:57:24,291
<i>Follow every rainbow</i>

1380
01:57:24,904 --> 01:57:28,931
<i>Till you find</i>

1381
01:57:29,242 --> 01:57:38,401
<i>Your dream</i>

1382
01:57:41,721 --> 01:57:45,248
Now, it's not like my children
to be secretive.

1383
01:57:45,458 --> 01:57:47,551
We're not being secretive, Father.

1384
01:57:49,262 --> 01:57:52,595
And it's not like my children
to be late for dinner.

1385
01:57:52,832 --> 01:57:56,290
- We lost track of the time.
- I see.

1386
01:57:57,103 --> 01:58:00,493
Who's going to be the first one
to tell me the truth? Friedrich.

1387
01:58:00,773 --> 01:58:02,798
Brigitta. Liesl.

1388
01:58:04,210 --> 01:58:06,405
Where do you think we were, Father?

1389
01:58:13,019 --> 01:58:16,978
If you don't believe us, you must have
some idea of where you think we were.

1390
01:58:20,593 --> 01:58:22,356
- Marta.
- Yes, Father.

1391
01:58:22,595 --> 01:58:23,823
You tell me.

1392
01:58:25,131 --> 01:58:28,794
Friedrich told you, Father.
We were berry picking.

1393
01:58:29,635 --> 01:58:34,265
- I forgot! You were berry picking.
- Yes, we love berry picking.

1394
01:58:34,607 --> 01:58:35,733
All afternoon?

1395
01:58:35,975 --> 01:58:37,670
- We picked thousands.
- Thousands?

1396
01:58:37,877 --> 01:58:40,801
- They were all over the place.
- What kind of berries?

1397
01:58:41,047 --> 01:58:44,346
- Blueberries, sir.
- Blueberries.

1398
01:58:46,285 --> 01:58:49,641
It's too early for blueberries.

1399
01:58:51,124 --> 01:58:53,183
- They were strawberries.
- Strawberries?

1400
01:58:53,960 --> 01:58:56,656
It's been so cold lately,
they turned blue.

1401
01:59:02,468 --> 01:59:04,663
Very well. Show me the berries.

1402
01:59:05,872 --> 01:59:07,134
- We...
- Well...

1403
01:59:07,373 --> 01:59:10,137
- Show me the berries you picked.
- We don't have them.

1404
01:59:10,376 --> 01:59:12,640
You don't have them?
What happened to them?

1405
01:59:12,879 --> 01:59:15,677
- We...
- We ate them.

1406
01:59:15,882 --> 01:59:18,476
- You ate them?
- Yes!

1407
01:59:18,684 --> 01:59:20,276
- They were so good.
- Delicious.

1408
01:59:20,486 --> 01:59:21,714
Very well.

1409
01:59:21,988 --> 01:59:27,085
Since you've obviously stuffed
yourselves on thousands of berries...

1410
01:59:27,360 --> 01:59:31,285
...you can't be hungry anymore,
so I'll have to tell Frau Schmidt...

1411
01:59:31,531 --> 01:59:34,386
...to skip your dinner.

1412
01:59:43,576 --> 01:59:46,340
It's your fault.
We should have told him the truth.

1413
01:59:46,579 --> 01:59:48,570
And made him boiling mad at us?

1414
01:59:48,814 --> 01:59:50,702
It's better than starving to death.

1415
01:59:50,950 --> 01:59:53,805
We didn't do anything wrong.
We just wanted to see her.

1416
01:59:55,121 --> 01:59:58,249
My stomach's making noises.

1417
01:59:58,691 --> 02:00:01,524
The least they could have done
was to let us say hello.

1418
02:00:02,628 --> 02:00:05,586
- I wonder what grass tastes like.
- I feel awful.

1419
02:00:08,000 --> 02:00:11,299
When Fräulein Maria wanted to feel
better she used to sing that song.

1420
02:00:11,904 --> 02:00:13,394
Let's try it.

1421
02:00:13,606 --> 02:00:16,268
<i>Raindrops on roses</i>

1422
02:00:16,509 --> 02:00:19,740
<i>And whiskers on kittens</i>

1423
02:00:21,447 --> 02:00:23,972
<i>Bright copper kettles</i>

1424
02:00:24,250 --> 02:00:27,276
<i>And warm woolen mittens</i>

1425
02:00:28,654 --> 02:00:34,149
<i>Brown paper packages
Tied up with strings</i>

1426
02:00:34,894 --> 02:00:39,991
<i>These are a few of my favorite things</i>

1427
02:00:41,133 --> 02:00:43,158
Why don't I feel better?

1428
02:00:44,337 --> 02:00:46,635
<i>Girls in white dresses</i>

1429
02:00:46,906 --> 02:00:49,898
<i>With blue satin sashes</i>

1430
02:00:50,209 --> 02:00:55,897
<i>Snowflakes that stay
On my nose and eyelashes</i>

1431
02:00:56,282 --> 02:00:59,410
- <i>Silver white winters</i>
- Fräulein Maria's back!

1432
02:00:59,619 --> 02:01:00,950
<i>That melt into springs</i>

1433
02:01:01,354 --> 02:01:04,551
<i>These are a few of my favorite things</i>

1434
02:01:04,824 --> 02:01:07,918
<i>When the dog bites
When the bee stings</i>

1435
02:01:08,160 --> 02:01:10,287
<i>When I'm feeling sad</i>

1436
02:01:10,730 --> 02:01:13,722
<i>I simply remember my favorite things</i>

1437
02:01:14,000 --> 02:01:16,230
<i>And then I don't feel</i>

1438
02:01:16,502 --> 02:01:22,828
<i>So bad</i>

1439
02:01:24,944 --> 02:01:26,536
- I'm so glad to see you.
- We missed you.

1440
02:01:26,746 --> 02:01:27,838
I missed you.

1441
02:01:28,080 --> 02:01:30,207
- Kurt, how are you?
- Hungry.

1442
02:01:31,751 --> 02:01:34,379
- What happened to your finger?
- It got caught.

1443
02:01:34,620 --> 02:01:36,781
- Caught in what?
- Friedrich's teeth.

1444
02:01:38,024 --> 02:01:40,219
- Liesl, you all right?
- Just fair.

1445
02:01:40,426 --> 02:01:43,384
- Any telegrams been delivered lately?
- None at all.

1446
02:01:43,629 --> 02:01:47,087
But I'm learning to accept it.
I'll be glad when school begins.

1447
02:01:47,366 --> 02:01:52,099
Liesl, you can't use school to escape
your problems. You have to face them.

1448
02:01:52,305 --> 02:01:53,704
I have so much to tell you.

1449
02:01:53,873 --> 02:01:55,932
- We have things to tell you too.
- I'm sure.

1450
02:01:56,275 --> 02:01:59,938
The most important thing is
that Father is going to be married.

1451
02:02:00,212 --> 02:02:01,236
Married?

1452
02:02:01,580 --> 02:02:03,605
Yes, to Baroness Schraeder.

1453
02:02:11,524 --> 02:02:13,082
Oh, I see.

1454
02:02:14,927 --> 02:02:18,283
Father, look!
Fräulein Maria's back!

1455
02:02:18,531 --> 02:02:20,556
Fräulein Maria's back from the abbey.

1456
02:02:22,768 --> 02:02:23,826
Good evening, captain.

1457
02:02:25,338 --> 02:02:26,635
Good evening.

1458
02:02:29,141 --> 02:02:31,029
Everyone inside for dinner.

1459
02:02:31,277 --> 02:02:32,904
Dinner!

1460
02:02:42,254 --> 02:02:46,918
You left without saying goodbye.
Even to the children.

1461
02:02:47,927 --> 02:02:49,485
It was wrong of me. Forgive me.

1462
02:02:51,564 --> 02:02:52,690
Why did you?

1463
02:02:52,932 --> 02:02:55,765
Please don't ask me.
The reason no longer exists.

1464
02:02:56,936 --> 02:02:59,996
Fräulein Maria, you've returned.

1465
02:03:01,207 --> 02:03:03,072
Isn't it wonderful, Georg?

1466
02:03:06,345 --> 02:03:08,575
I wish you every happiness, baroness.

1467
02:03:08,781 --> 02:03:11,614
You too, captain.
The children say you're to marry.

1468
02:03:11,784 --> 02:03:12,842
Thank you, my dear.

1469
02:03:15,454 --> 02:03:18,981
You are back to stay?

1470
02:03:21,093 --> 02:03:24,392
Only until arrangements can be made
for another governess.

1471
02:04:20,186 --> 02:04:21,778
There you are.

1472
02:04:36,168 --> 02:04:38,693
I must speak to cook
about the schnitzel.

1473
02:04:38,938 --> 02:04:42,237
It is entirely too delicious
for my figure.

1474
02:04:42,675 --> 02:04:45,599
And it makes you much too quiet
at the dinner table.

1475
02:04:45,878 --> 02:04:47,869
Or was it the wine?

1476
02:04:48,113 --> 02:04:49,944
Undoubtedly the wine.

1477
02:04:52,485 --> 02:04:54,783
You have no idea
the trouble I'm having...

1478
02:04:55,054 --> 02:04:57,784
...trying to decide on
a wedding present for you.

1479
02:04:58,057 --> 02:05:00,218
Oh, I know. I'm enough.

1480
02:05:00,459 --> 02:05:04,122
But I do want you to have
some little trifle for the occasion.

1481
02:05:04,330 --> 02:05:06,696
At first I thought
of a fountain pen...

1482
02:05:06,932 --> 02:05:09,196
...but you've already got one.

1483
02:05:09,435 --> 02:05:12,393
Then I thought perhaps a villa
in the south of France...

1484
02:05:12,638 --> 02:05:15,300
...but they are so difficult
to gift-wrap.

1485
02:05:15,574 --> 02:05:17,963
Oh, Georg, how do you
feel about yachts?

1486
02:05:18,244 --> 02:05:20,508
A long, sleek one
for the Mediterranean...

1487
02:05:20,779 --> 02:05:23,509
...or a tiny one
for your bathtub, huh?

1488
02:05:25,718 --> 02:05:27,743
- Elsa.
- Where to go on our honeymoon?

1489
02:05:27,987 --> 02:05:29,579
Now, that's a real problem.

1490
02:05:29,788 --> 02:05:33,144
A trip around the world
would be lovely. And then I said:

1491
02:05:33,425 --> 02:05:36,280
"Oh, Elsa, there must be
someplace better to go."

1492
02:05:36,529 --> 02:05:38,952
- But don't worry, darling, I'll--
- Elsa.

1493
02:05:39,665 --> 02:05:40,859
Yes, Georg.

1494
02:05:41,934 --> 02:05:43,231
It's no use...

1495
02:05:44,470 --> 02:05:45,835
...you and I.

1496
02:05:47,373 --> 02:05:50,638
I'm being dishonest to both of us...

1497
02:05:51,977 --> 02:05:53,604
...and utterly unfair to you.

1498
02:05:58,851 --> 02:06:01,649
- When two people talk of marriage--
- No, don't.

1499
02:06:02,521 --> 02:06:04,614
Don't say another word, please.

1500
02:06:07,893 --> 02:06:12,956
You see, there are other things
I've been thinking of.

1501
02:06:13,866 --> 02:06:18,565
Fond as I am of you, I really don't
think you're the right man for me.

1502
02:06:21,140 --> 02:06:23,563
You're much too independent.

1503
02:06:23,876 --> 02:06:28,631
And I need someone
who needs me desperately...

1504
02:06:28,881 --> 02:06:31,907
...or at least needs
my money desperately.

1505
02:06:34,086 --> 02:06:39,012
I've enjoyed every moment we've had
together and I do thank you for that.

1506
02:06:41,794 --> 02:06:43,659
Now, if you'll forgive me...

1507
02:06:43,896 --> 02:06:45,921
...I'll go inside,
pack my little bags...

1508
02:06:46,198 --> 02:06:48,689
...and return to Vienna
where I belong.

1509
02:06:54,073 --> 02:06:55,904
And somewhere out there...

1510
02:06:56,175 --> 02:06:59,008
...is a young lady who, I think...

1511
02:07:00,846 --> 02:07:02,074
...will never be a nun.

1512
02:07:14,226 --> 02:07:16,558
Auf Wiedersehen, darling.

1513
02:07:42,287 --> 02:07:43,447
Hello.

1514
02:07:49,261 --> 02:07:52,856
I thought I just might find you here.

1515
02:07:57,002 --> 02:07:59,300
Was there something you wanted?

1516
02:07:59,672 --> 02:08:02,869
No, no, no. Sit down, please.

1517
02:08:03,776 --> 02:08:05,141
Please.

1518
02:08:10,249 --> 02:08:11,614
May I?

1519
02:08:23,996 --> 02:08:28,695
You know, I was thinking
and I was wondering two things:

1520
02:08:29,835 --> 02:08:34,124
Why did you run away to the abbey?

1521
02:08:34,940 --> 02:08:39,639
And what was it
that made you come back?

1522
02:08:41,313 --> 02:08:45,704
Well, I had an obligation
to fulfill...

1523
02:08:45,984 --> 02:08:48,111
...and I came back to fulfill it.

1524
02:08:48,721 --> 02:08:50,211
Is that all?

1525
02:08:51,523 --> 02:08:53,650
And I missed the children.

1526
02:08:53,992 --> 02:08:55,186
Yes.

1527
02:08:56,462 --> 02:08:59,351
- Only the children?
- No. Yes.

1528
02:08:59,565 --> 02:09:03,353
- Isn't it right that I missed them?
- Oh, yes. Yes, of course.

1529
02:09:03,635 --> 02:09:06,229
I was only hoping that perhaps you...

1530
02:09:07,372 --> 02:09:09,135
Perhaps you might...

1531
02:09:10,876 --> 02:09:12,070
Yes?

1532
02:09:13,846 --> 02:09:19,170
Well, nothing was the same
when you were away...

1533
02:09:19,885 --> 02:09:23,150
...and it'll be all wrong again
after you leave...

1534
02:09:23,388 --> 02:09:28,052
...and I just thought perhaps
you might change your mind.

1535
02:09:32,097 --> 02:09:36,329
Well, I'm sure the baroness will be
able to make things fine for you.

1536
02:09:36,568 --> 02:09:37,967
Maria...

1537
02:09:40,072 --> 02:09:43,564
- There isn't going to be any baroness.
- There isn't?

1538
02:09:45,978 --> 02:09:47,343
No.

1539
02:09:47,613 --> 02:09:49,410
I don't understand.

1540
02:09:51,784 --> 02:09:55,914
Well, we've called off our engagement,
you see, and--

1541
02:09:56,188 --> 02:09:59,612
- Oh, I'm sorry.
- Yes. You are?

1542
02:10:00,759 --> 02:10:02,989
- You did?
- Yes.

1543
02:10:04,062 --> 02:10:08,590
Well, you can't marry someone
when you're...

1544
02:10:11,103 --> 02:10:13,196
...in love with someone else...

1545
02:10:16,608 --> 02:10:18,041
...can you?

1546
02:10:52,911 --> 02:10:55,175
The Reverend Mother always says:

1547
02:10:55,447 --> 02:10:58,837
"When the Lord closes a door,
somewhere he opens a window."

1548
02:11:07,259 --> 02:11:10,319
What else does
the Reverend Mother say?

1549
02:11:11,263 --> 02:11:13,652
That you have to look for your life.

1550
02:11:15,334 --> 02:11:17,825
Is that why you came back?

1551
02:11:21,874 --> 02:11:23,364
And have you found it...

1552
02:11:24,376 --> 02:11:25,570
...Maria?

1553
02:11:27,312 --> 02:11:29,303
I think I have.

1554
02:11:31,783 --> 02:11:32,647
I know I have.

1555
02:11:35,921 --> 02:11:37,582
I love you.

1556
02:11:41,560 --> 02:11:44,051
Oh, can this be happening to me?

1557
02:11:46,798 --> 02:11:52,156
<i>Perhaps I had a wicked childhood</i>

1558
02:11:53,672 --> 02:11:58,928
<i>Perhaps I had a miserable youth</i>

1559
02:12:00,245 --> 02:12:06,536
<i>But somewhere
In my wicked, miserable past</i>

1560
02:12:07,252 --> 02:12:12,849
<i>There must have been a moment of truth</i>

1561
02:12:13,959 --> 02:12:20,182
<i>For here you are
Standing there loving me</i>

1562
02:12:21,466 --> 02:12:27,496
<i>Whether or not you should</i>

1563
02:12:28,140 --> 02:12:34,932
<i>So somewhere in my youth or childhood</i>

1564
02:12:35,781 --> 02:12:43,438
<i>I must have done something good</i>

1565
02:12:44,690 --> 02:12:47,648
<i>Nothing comes from nothing</i>

1566
02:12:48,794 --> 02:12:52,616
<i>Nothing ever could</i>

1567
02:12:53,498 --> 02:13:02,361
<i>So somewhere in my youth or childhood</i>

1568
02:13:03,875 --> 02:13:13,364
<i>I must have done something good</i>

1569
02:13:14,319 --> 02:13:19,143
Do you know when I first
started loving you?

1570
02:13:19,558 --> 02:13:23,415
That night at dinner, when you sat
on that ridiculous pine cone.

1571
02:13:23,695 --> 02:13:24,992
What?

1572
02:13:26,331 --> 02:13:29,755
I knew the first time you blew
that silly whistle.

1573
02:13:30,702 --> 02:13:32,693
Oh, my love.

1574
02:13:36,441 --> 02:13:44,166
<i>For here you are
Standing there loving me</i>

1575
02:13:46,351 --> 02:13:51,744
<i>Whether or not you should</i>

1576
02:13:53,558 --> 02:14:00,589
<i>So somewhere in my youth or childhood</i>

1577
02:14:01,366 --> 02:14:09,091
<i>I must have done something good</i>

1578
02:14:10,275 --> 02:14:13,403
<i>Nothing comes from nothing</i>

1579
02:14:14,413 --> 02:14:17,541
<i>Nothing ever could</i>

1580
02:14:17,783 --> 02:14:23,176
<i>So somewhere in my youth</i>

1581
02:14:23,822 --> 02:14:26,086
<i>Or childhood</i>

1582
02:14:29,194 --> 02:14:35,326
<i>I must have done something</i>

1583
02:14:37,769 --> 02:14:50,432
<i>Something good</i>

1584
02:14:57,122 --> 02:14:58,612
Maria.

1585
02:15:00,492 --> 02:15:05,088
Is there anyone I should go to,
to ask permission to marry you?

1586
02:15:09,000 --> 02:15:10,797
- Why don't we ask--
- The children?

1587
02:17:01,179 --> 02:17:04,103
<i>How do you solve a problem like Maria?</i>

1588
02:17:04,916 --> 02:17:08,477
<i>How do you catch a cloud
And pin it down?</i>

1589
02:17:09,521 --> 02:17:13,787
<i>How do you find a word
That means Maria?</i>

1590
02:17:14,159 --> 02:17:15,183
<i>A flibbertigibbet</i>

1591
02:17:15,427 --> 02:17:18,692
<i>A will-o'-the-wisp
A clown</i>

1592
02:17:18,930 --> 02:17:22,889
<i>Many a thing you know
You'd like to tell her</i>

1593
02:17:23,902 --> 02:17:27,668
<i>Many a thing she ought to understand</i>

1594
02:17:28,673 --> 02:17:32,666
<i>But how do you make her stay
And listen to all you say?</i>

1595
02:17:33,345 --> 02:17:37,270
<i>How do you keep a wave upon the sand?</i>

1596
02:17:37,616 --> 02:17:41,609
<i>Oh, how do you solve
A problem like Maria?</i>

1597
02:17:42,988 --> 02:17:49,621
<i>How do you hold a moonbeam
In your hand?</i>

1598
02:19:55,687 --> 02:19:57,279
Herr Detweiler!

1599
02:19:59,858 --> 02:20:02,554
- Heil Hitler.
- Oh, good afternoon, Herr Zeller.

1600
02:20:02,794 --> 02:20:06,093
Perhaps you've not heard.
I am now the Gauleiter.

1601
02:20:06,331 --> 02:20:07,923
Heil Hitler.

1602
02:20:08,833 --> 02:20:09,993
Heil Hitler.

1603
02:20:10,268 --> 02:20:12,566
I've come from
Captain von Trapp's house.

1604
02:20:13,004 --> 02:20:16,599
The only one in the area
not flying the Third Reich flag...

1605
02:20:16,841 --> 02:20:18,069
...since the Anschluss.

1606
02:20:18,309 --> 02:20:20,470
- But we have dealt with that.
- I don't--

1607
02:20:20,712 --> 02:20:23,670
The housekeeper told me
that I would find you here.

1608
02:20:23,948 --> 02:20:25,643
The only thing she'd tell me.

1609
02:20:26,151 --> 02:20:28,676
What kind of information
are you looking for?

1610
02:20:28,953 --> 02:20:30,818
When will the captain return?

1611
02:20:31,356 --> 02:20:35,281
Well, he's on his honeymoon trip.
He's not been in touch with us.

1612
02:20:35,527 --> 02:20:40,351
Am I to believe he hasn't communicated
with his children in over a month?

1613
02:20:40,632 --> 02:20:42,520
How many men do you know...

1614
02:20:42,801 --> 02:20:46,100
...who communicate with their children
while honeymooning?

1615
02:20:46,971 --> 02:20:50,702
Upon his return, he'll fill
his proper position in the new order.

1616
02:20:50,975 --> 02:20:53,364
Naturally.
And may I congratulate you...

1617
02:20:53,645 --> 02:20:58,241
...and your people in allowing the
festival to go on tonight as planned.

1618
02:20:58,817 --> 02:21:02,241
Why should it not go on?
Nothing in Austria has changed.

1619
02:21:02,520 --> 02:21:05,876
Singing and music will
show this to the world.

1620
02:21:06,124 --> 02:21:07,751
Austria is the same.

1621
02:21:08,693 --> 02:21:10,058
Heil Hitler.

1622
02:21:12,230 --> 02:21:13,822
Heil Hitler.

1623
02:21:15,500 --> 02:21:16,728
Come, let's go home.

1624
02:21:16,935 --> 02:21:20,427
- Why was he so cross?
- Everybody's cross these days.

1625
02:21:20,672 --> 02:21:24,028
Maybe the flag with the black spider
makes people nervous.

1626
02:21:24,242 --> 02:21:27,166
- Will Father be in trouble?
- He doesn't have to be.

1627
02:21:27,412 --> 02:21:30,142
The thing to do
is to get along with everybody.

1628
02:21:30,381 --> 02:21:32,576
Remember that tonight at the concert.

1629
02:21:32,784 --> 02:21:35,708
Are we really going to sing
before a lot of people?

1630
02:21:35,920 --> 02:21:38,013
Look. The von Trapp Family Singers:

1631
02:21:38,223 --> 02:21:42,785
Liesl, Friedrich, Louisa, Brigitta,
Kurt, Marta and Gretl.

1632
02:21:43,027 --> 02:21:47,384
- Why am I always last?
- Because you are the most important.

1633
02:21:48,099 --> 02:21:49,691
There we go.

1634
02:21:55,607 --> 02:21:59,065
Are you sure Father will approve
of our singing in public?

1635
02:21:59,277 --> 02:22:01,575
He'll be pleased and proud.

1636
02:22:02,046 --> 02:22:04,469
- Liesl, do you think so?
- Don't you trust me?

1637
02:22:04,716 --> 02:22:05,740
No.

1638
02:22:05,950 --> 02:22:08,043
You're a very intelligent girl.

1639
02:22:08,553 --> 02:22:10,748
Liesl. Liesl!

1640
02:22:11,689 --> 02:22:12,883
Rolfe!

1641
02:22:13,892 --> 02:22:15,883
I'm so glad to see you.
It's been su--

1642
02:22:16,127 --> 02:22:17,219
Good afternoon.

1643
02:22:17,629 --> 02:22:20,553
Give this to your father
as soon as he's home.

1644
02:22:21,232 --> 02:22:23,097
- He's on his honeymoon.
- I know.

1645
02:22:23,301 --> 02:22:26,634
- You do?
- We make it our business to know all.

1646
02:22:27,305 --> 02:22:29,933
- Who's "we"?
- See that he gets it.

1647
02:22:30,141 --> 02:22:32,439
- What is it?
- It's a telegram from Berlin.

1648
02:22:33,311 --> 02:22:35,802
Don't you want to deliver it yourself?

1649
02:22:36,281 --> 02:22:38,909
I'm occupied
with more important matters.

1650
02:22:39,117 --> 02:22:41,608
And your father had better be too.

1651
02:22:41,819 --> 02:22:43,343
But, Rolfe!

1652
02:23:06,477 --> 02:23:08,138
Father!

1653
02:23:08,379 --> 02:23:11,041
- We didn't expect you so soon.
- Hello, hello!

1654
02:23:11,316 --> 02:23:14,114
We didn't expect you home
until next week!

1655
02:23:14,319 --> 02:23:19,746
- Did you bring souvenirs from Paris?
- Hello! How are you?

1656
02:23:20,858 --> 02:23:22,155
Why didn't you call us?

1657
02:23:22,360 --> 02:23:24,282
We couldn't get through.

1658
02:23:24,529 --> 02:23:26,485
I had nothing to do with that.

1659
02:23:26,764 --> 02:23:28,789
We came back as fast as we could.

1660
02:23:29,133 --> 02:23:31,294
Well, well, well! We missed you!

1661
02:23:31,536 --> 02:23:33,959
- We missed you!
- We missed kissing you.

1662
02:23:34,172 --> 02:23:37,005
We missed all the noise
in the morning.

1663
02:23:37,275 --> 02:23:41,473
- Mostly, we missed hearing you sing.
- Oh, you came back just in time.

1664
02:23:41,679 --> 02:23:43,374
Look, Fräulein Maria--

1665
02:23:43,648 --> 02:23:45,206
I mean Mother.

1666
02:23:45,683 --> 02:23:48,174
We're going to sing
in the festival tonight.

1667
02:23:48,386 --> 02:23:50,479
We've been having a lovely time!

1668
02:23:50,722 --> 02:23:52,815
We've been rehearsing all--

1669
02:23:54,359 --> 02:23:56,691
Surprise! Surprise!

1670
02:23:57,362 --> 02:23:59,853
Surprises for you on the terrace.

1671
02:24:02,900 --> 02:24:04,231
We'll talk about this.

1672
02:24:04,502 --> 02:24:08,791
I would've told you but you were away.
I had to make a last-minute decision.

1673
02:24:09,073 --> 02:24:11,564
I was fortunate to enter them at all.

1674
02:24:11,809 --> 02:24:16,508
They'll be the talk of the festival.
Imagine, seven children in one family!

1675
02:24:16,714 --> 02:24:18,375
Max!

1676
02:24:18,950 --> 02:24:21,805
Somehow I recall having made it
quite clear to you...

1677
02:24:22,053 --> 02:24:24,749
...how I feel about my family
singing in public!

1678
02:24:25,023 --> 02:24:26,718
The committee was enchanted.

1679
02:24:26,924 --> 02:24:30,087
- What did they say?
- I have never heard such enthusiasm.

1680
02:24:30,361 --> 02:24:34,627
- Don't you think just this once--?
- Absolutely out of the question.

1681
02:24:34,899 --> 02:24:39,029
- Georg, this is for Austria.
- For Austria?

1682
02:24:39,404 --> 02:24:42,601
- There is no Austria!
- But the Anschluss was peaceful.

1683
02:24:42,874 --> 02:24:46,366
- Let's at least be grateful for that.
- Grateful?

1684
02:24:48,246 --> 02:24:49,873
You know, Max...

1685
02:24:50,782 --> 02:24:53,979
...sometimes I don't believe
I know you.

1686
02:24:56,721 --> 02:24:58,086
Father, I forgot.

1687
02:24:58,923 --> 02:25:00,481
This is for you.

1688
02:25:10,301 --> 02:25:14,294
Maria, he has got to at least pretend
to work with these people.

1689
02:25:14,572 --> 02:25:16,062
You must convince him.

1690
02:25:16,307 --> 02:25:19,071
Max, I can't ask him
to be less than he is.

1691
02:25:19,277 --> 02:25:22,610
Then I'll talk to him.
If the children don't sing, well...

1692
02:25:22,880 --> 02:25:25,110
...it will be a reflection
on Austria.

1693
02:25:25,917 --> 02:25:29,273
Oh, I know.
It wouldn't do me any good either.

1694
02:25:34,459 --> 02:25:37,121
Mother? That sounds so nice.

1695
02:25:37,395 --> 02:25:40,125
- I like calling you "Mother."
- I like hearing it.

1696
02:25:40,331 --> 02:25:43,926
You love Father very much.
I can tell you do.

1697
02:25:44,102 --> 02:25:45,126
Very much.

1698
02:25:45,303 --> 02:25:48,636
Mother, what do you do when you
think you love someone?

1699
02:25:49,307 --> 02:25:54,597
I mean, when you stop loving someone
or he stops loving you?

1700
02:25:57,215 --> 02:25:59,308
Well, you cry a little.

1701
02:25:59,717 --> 02:26:01,844
Then you wait for the sun
to come out.

1702
02:26:02,120 --> 02:26:03,485
It always does.

1703
02:26:03,721 --> 02:26:07,282
There are so many things I think
I should know but I don't.

1704
02:26:07,525 --> 02:26:09,481
- I really don't.
- How can you?

1705
02:26:09,827 --> 02:26:13,957
- Sometimes I feel the world is ending.
- Then you feel it's just beginning?

1706
02:26:14,132 --> 02:26:16,794
- Yes!
- It was that way with me.

1707
02:26:17,235 --> 02:26:21,467
- And for you it will be just as wonderful.
- Do you really think so?

1708
02:26:23,608 --> 02:26:27,271
<i>When you're 16 going on 17</i>

1709
02:26:27,512 --> 02:26:31,107
<i>Waiting for life to start</i>

1710
02:26:31,783 --> 02:26:35,605
<i>Somebody kind
Who touches your mind</i>

1711
02:26:35,853 --> 02:26:40,142
<i>Will suddenly touch your heart</i>

1712
02:26:40,558 --> 02:26:42,287
<i>When that happens</i>

1713
02:26:42,693 --> 02:26:44,649
<i>After it happens</i>

1714
02:26:44,929 --> 02:26:48,285
<i>Nothing is quite the same</i>

1715
02:26:49,000 --> 02:26:50,558
<i>Somehow I know</i>

1716
02:26:50,835 --> 02:26:52,826
<i>I'll jump up and go</i>

1717
02:26:53,237 --> 02:26:57,196
<i>If ever he calls my name</i>

1718
02:26:57,742 --> 02:27:01,667
<i>Gone are your old ideas of life</i>

1719
02:27:01,946 --> 02:27:05,575
<i>The old ideas grow dim</i>

1720
02:27:06,250 --> 02:27:10,482
<i>Lo and behold
You're someone's wife</i>

1721
02:27:11,722 --> 02:27:17,547
<i>And you belong to him</i>

1722
02:27:17,995 --> 02:27:22,056
<i>You may think this kind of adventure</i>

1723
02:27:22,533 --> 02:27:26,390
<i>Never may come to you</i>

1724
02:27:27,471 --> 02:27:32,363
<i>Darling, 16 going on 17</i>

1725
02:27:33,711 --> 02:27:37,841
<i>Wait a year</i>

1726
02:27:38,616 --> 02:27:43,872
- <i>I'll wait a year</i>
- <i>Or two</i>

1727
02:27:44,255 --> 02:27:51,252
<i>Just wait a year</i>

1728
02:27:52,530 --> 02:28:00,722
<i>Or two</i>

1729
02:28:21,592 --> 02:28:22,957
What is it?

1730
02:28:23,895 --> 02:28:25,260
Berlin.

1731
02:28:25,730 --> 02:28:27,595
They've offered me a commission.

1732
02:28:27,832 --> 02:28:30,392
I've been requested
to accept immediately...

1733
02:28:30,635 --> 02:28:34,628
...and report to their naval base
at Bremerhaven tomorrow.

1734
02:28:35,239 --> 02:28:39,232
I knew this would happen.
I didn't think it would be so soon.

1735
02:28:39,443 --> 02:28:42,970
To refuse them would be fatal
for all of us.

1736
02:28:44,181 --> 02:28:47,969
And joining them would be unthinkable.

1737
02:28:54,125 --> 02:28:55,922
Get the children all together.

1738
02:28:56,193 --> 02:28:59,458
Don't say anything to worry them.
Just get them ready.

1739
02:29:00,364 --> 02:29:02,787
We've got to get out of Austria...

1740
02:29:04,435 --> 02:29:06,130
...and this house...

1741
02:29:08,472 --> 02:29:09,871
...tonight.

1742
02:29:53,818 --> 02:29:56,207
This strains my back
and breaks my heart...

1743
02:29:56,487 --> 02:29:59,320
...when I think of the children
missing the festival.

1744
02:29:59,557 --> 02:30:02,253
By your announcement
we'll be over the border.

1745
02:30:02,526 --> 02:30:04,915
Do you appreciate
the sacrifice I'm making?

1746
02:30:05,162 --> 02:30:06,424
You have no choice.

1747
02:30:06,697 --> 02:30:09,530
I know. That's why I'm making it.

1748
02:30:10,201 --> 02:30:12,362
Why doesn't Father turn the motor on?

1749
02:30:12,570 --> 02:30:15,994
Because he doesn't want anyone
to hear us.

1750
02:30:19,577 --> 02:30:22,068
What will Frau Schmidt and Franz say?

1751
02:30:22,346 --> 02:30:25,838
They'll be able to answer honestly
they didn't know anything.

1752
02:30:26,083 --> 02:30:30,281
- Will we be coming back here?
- Someday, Liesl. I do hope someday.

1753
02:30:30,554 --> 02:30:35,446
Are Father and Uncle Max going to push
the car all the way to Switzerland?

1754
02:31:02,253 --> 02:31:04,676
Something wrong
with your car, captain?

1755
02:31:04,989 --> 02:31:07,287
Yes, we couldn't get it started.

1756
02:31:11,062 --> 02:31:12,290
Karl.

1757
02:31:14,265 --> 02:31:17,723
Fix Captain von Trapp's car
so that it will start.

1758
02:31:40,925 --> 02:31:42,756
Excellent, Karl.

1759
02:31:46,130 --> 02:31:49,258
I've not asked you where you
and your family are going.

1760
02:31:49,800 --> 02:31:51,927
Nor have you asked me why I'm here.

1761
02:31:52,136 --> 02:31:55,867
Apparently we both suffer
from a deplorable lack of curiosity.

1762
02:31:56,774 --> 02:31:59,265
You never answered the telegram...

1763
02:31:59,477 --> 02:32:02,776
...from the Admiral of the Navy
of the Third Reich.

1764
02:32:03,013 --> 02:32:05,504
I was under the impression,
Herr Zeller...

1765
02:32:05,683 --> 02:32:09,244
...that the contents of telegrams
in Austria are private!

1766
02:32:09,954 --> 02:32:13,481
At least, the Austria I know.

1767
02:32:14,625 --> 02:32:16,252
I have my orders...

1768
02:32:16,494 --> 02:32:18,655
...to take you
to Bremerhaven tonight...

1769
02:32:18,896 --> 02:32:21,126
...where you will accept
your commission.

1770
02:32:22,266 --> 02:32:27,659
I'm afraid that's going to be
quite impossible.

1771
02:32:28,305 --> 02:32:30,000
You see, we...

1772
02:32:30,574 --> 02:32:33,407
...all of us, the entire family,
will be...

1773
02:32:34,512 --> 02:32:36,537
...singing in the festival tonight.

1774
02:32:36,847 --> 02:32:39,270
As a matter of fact, we're going now.

1775
02:32:39,917 --> 02:32:42,806
We couldn't possibly
let them down now.

1776
02:32:43,020 --> 02:32:45,978
- I just hope we're not too late.
- Yes.

1777
02:32:46,223 --> 02:32:49,078
You ask me to believe that you,
Captain von Trapp...

1778
02:32:49,360 --> 02:32:50,850
...are singing in a concert?

1779
02:32:51,228 --> 02:32:55,358
Believe me, it will be a performance
beyond anything even I've dreamt of.

1780
02:32:55,699 --> 02:33:00,363
Like you, Herr Zeller,
I, too, am a man of hidden talents.

1781
02:33:01,038 --> 02:33:02,403
Yes.

1782
02:33:02,673 --> 02:33:05,096
Here, program.

1783
02:33:10,181 --> 02:33:12,445
It says only the names
of the children.

1784
02:33:12,716 --> 02:33:16,015
It says
the von Trapp Family Singers...

1785
02:33:16,253 --> 02:33:19,313
...and I am the head of
the von Trapp family, am I not?

1786
02:33:21,592 --> 02:33:25,380
And these travel clothes
that you're all wearing?

1787
02:33:26,230 --> 02:33:27,754
Our costumes, naturally.

1788
02:33:28,032 --> 02:33:31,388
This night air is not good
for the children's voices.

1789
02:33:37,641 --> 02:33:41,202
Well, a slight delay in my orders
will not be serious.

1790
02:33:42,413 --> 02:33:43,903
Therefore...

1791
02:33:44,782 --> 02:33:46,409
...you will sing.

1792
02:33:47,351 --> 02:33:49,342
You will all sing.

1793
02:33:49,720 --> 02:33:52,245
But only because that's what I want.

1794
02:33:53,123 --> 02:33:56,615
It will demonstrate that nothing
in Austria has changed.

1795
02:33:57,361 --> 02:33:59,556
And when you have finished singing...

1796
02:33:59,863 --> 02:34:02,991
...you, Captain von Trapp, will be
taken to Bremerhaven.

1797
02:34:04,301 --> 02:34:07,065
Now, if you will all get
into your car...

1798
02:34:07,271 --> 02:34:11,059
...we will escort the von Trapp Family
Singers to the festival.

1799
02:34:11,942 --> 02:34:14,137
No escort will be necessary.

1800
02:34:14,411 --> 02:34:16,902
Necessary? A pleasure, captain.

1801
02:34:17,781 --> 02:34:21,638
After all, we would not want you
to get lost in the crowds.

1802
02:34:22,886 --> 02:34:24,376
Would we?

1803
02:34:25,022 --> 02:34:26,182
No.

1804
02:34:43,407 --> 02:34:45,602
- <i>Sew, a needle pulling thread</i>
- <i>A needle pulling thread</i>

1805
02:34:45,809 --> 02:34:48,698
- <i>La, a note to follow sew</i>
- <i>A note to follow sew</i>

1806
02:34:48,912 --> 02:34:52,700
- <i>Tea, a drink with jam and bread</i>
- <i>A drink with jam and bread</i>

1807
02:34:52,950 --> 02:34:55,783
- <i>A drink with jam and bread</i>
- <i>A drink with jam and bread</i>

1808
02:34:55,953 --> 02:34:57,477
- <i>Jam and bread</i>
- <i>With jam and bread</i>

1809
02:34:57,655 --> 02:34:59,145
<i>Tea with jam and bread</i>

1810
02:34:59,323 --> 02:35:01,689
<i>Tea with jam and bread
Jam and bread</i>

1811
02:35:01,859 --> 02:35:04,953
<i>Jam and bread
Tea with jam, jam and bread</i>

1812
02:35:05,129 --> 02:35:08,428
<i>Jam and bread
Tea with jam, jam and bread</i>

1813
02:35:14,371 --> 02:35:17,704
- <i>With jam</i>
- <i>A, B, C</i>

1814
02:35:17,941 --> 02:35:21,172
- <i>With jam</i>
- <i>Do-re-mi</i>

1815
02:35:21,378 --> 02:35:24,973
<i>Tea with jam and bread</i>

1816
02:35:25,215 --> 02:35:26,546
<i>With jam and bread</i>

1817
02:35:26,817 --> 02:35:28,341
<i>With jam
With jam</i>

1818
02:35:28,552 --> 02:35:36,379
<i>And bread</i>

1819
02:35:59,316 --> 02:36:02,513
My fellow Austrians...

1820
02:36:03,821 --> 02:36:08,315
...I shall not be seeing you again,
perhaps for a very long time.

1821
02:36:09,760 --> 02:36:11,557
I would like to sing for you now...

1822
02:36:13,030 --> 02:36:14,588
...a love song.

1823
02:36:16,567 --> 02:36:18,762
I know you share this love.

1824
02:36:20,070 --> 02:36:23,767
I pray that you will never let it die.

1825
02:36:36,520 --> 02:36:39,614
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1826
02:36:40,224 --> 02:36:42,818
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1827
02:36:43,727 --> 02:36:49,120
<i>Every morning you greet me</i>

1828
02:36:49,833 --> 02:36:52,529
<i>Small and white</i>

1829
02:36:53,170 --> 02:36:55,968
<i>Clean and bright</i>

1830
02:36:56,540 --> 02:37:01,637
<i>You look happy to meet me</i>

1831
02:37:02,413 --> 02:37:04,301
<i>Blossom of snow</i>

1832
02:37:04,481 --> 02:37:07,905
<i>May you bloom and grow</i>

1833
02:37:08,552 --> 02:37:14,184
<i>Bloom and grow forever</i>

1834
02:37:15,659 --> 02:37:17,422
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1835
02:37:18,462 --> 02:37:20,123
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1836
02:37:21,298 --> 02:37:27,294
<i>Bless my homeland forever</i>

1837
02:37:31,809 --> 02:37:34,300
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1838
02:37:35,145 --> 02:37:36,476
<i>Edel...</i>

1839
02:37:43,854 --> 02:37:46,948
<i>Small and white</i>

1840
02:37:47,157 --> 02:37:49,990
<i>Clean and bright</i>

1841
02:37:50,227 --> 02:37:55,585
<i>You look happy to meet me</i>

1842
02:37:56,400 --> 02:37:58,288
<i>Blossom of snow</i>

1843
02:37:58,469 --> 02:38:01,996
<i>May you bloom and grow</i>

1844
02:38:02,673 --> 02:38:08,634
<i>Bloom and grow forever</i>

1845
02:38:09,146 --> 02:38:12,001
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1846
02:38:12,349 --> 02:38:15,045
<i>Edelweiss</i>

1847
02:38:15,719 --> 02:38:23,911
<i>Bless my homeland forever</i>

1848
02:38:41,712 --> 02:38:43,270
I think it'll work.

1849
02:38:43,981 --> 02:38:45,778
I shall miss all of you.

1850
02:38:46,250 --> 02:38:48,741
I shall miss the money
I could have made with you.

1851
02:38:52,122 --> 02:38:53,612
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.

1852
02:38:54,424 --> 02:38:57,086
The competition has come
to its conclusion...

1853
02:38:57,327 --> 02:39:00,455
...except, we don't know
yet what that conclusion will be.

1854
02:39:01,431 --> 02:39:03,956
And while the judges
arrive at their decision...

1855
02:39:04,234 --> 02:39:07,260
...I have been given permission
to offer you an encore.

1856
02:39:07,504 --> 02:39:10,735
This will be the last opportunity
the von Trapps will have...

1857
02:39:10,974 --> 02:39:13,340
...of singing together
for a long, long time.

1858
02:39:14,444 --> 02:39:18,437
Even now, officials are waiting
in this auditorium...

1859
02:39:18,715 --> 02:39:21,411
...to escort Captain von Trapp
to his new command...

1860
02:39:21,618 --> 02:39:25,213
...in the naval forces
of the Third Reich.

1861
02:39:29,860 --> 02:39:34,354
And so, ladies and gentlemen,
the family von Trapp again...

1862
02:39:35,032 --> 02:39:37,125
...to bid you farewell.

1863
02:39:44,508 --> 02:39:48,137
<i>There's a sad sort of clanging
From the clock in the hall</i>

1864
02:39:48,412 --> 02:39:51,745
<i>And the bells in the steeple too</i>

1865
02:39:52,249 --> 02:39:56,071
<i>And up in the nursery
An absurd little bird</i>

1866
02:39:56,320 --> 02:39:58,743
<i>Is popping out to say "coo-coo"</i>

1867
02:39:58,956 --> 02:40:00,617
<i>Coo-coo</i>

1868
02:40:00,857 --> 02:40:01,915
<i>Coo-coo</i>

1869
02:40:02,125 --> 02:40:03,752
- <i>Regretfully, they tell us</i>
- <i>Coo-coo</i>

1870
02:40:03,961 --> 02:40:05,758
- <i>But firmly they compel us</i>
- <i>Coo-coo</i>

1871
02:40:05,996 --> 02:40:08,419
<i>To say goodbye</i>

1872
02:40:08,966 --> 02:40:14,131
<i>To you</i>

1873
02:40:17,040 --> 02:40:20,635
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, good night</i>

1874
02:40:20,844 --> 02:40:24,439
<i>We hate to go
And miss this pretty sight</i>

1875
02:40:30,821 --> 02:40:34,382
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, adieu</i>

1876
02:40:34,625 --> 02:40:38,117
<i>Adieu, adieu
To you and you and you</i>

1877
02:40:44,568 --> 02:40:48,163
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye</i>

1878
02:40:48,372 --> 02:40:49,862
<i>We flit, we float</i>

1879
02:40:50,273 --> 02:40:51,968
<i>We fleetly flee, we fly</i>

1880
02:40:58,348 --> 02:41:02,045
<i>So long, farewell
Auf Wiedersehen, goodbye</i>

1881
02:41:02,352 --> 02:41:05,708
<i>The sun has gone to bed
And so must I</i>

1882
02:41:05,989 --> 02:41:08,219
<i>Goodbye</i>

1883
02:41:10,027 --> 02:41:15,715
<i>Goodbye</i>

1884
02:41:15,932 --> 02:41:19,789
<i>Goodbye</i>

1885
02:41:21,338 --> 02:41:28,562
<i>Goodbye</i>

1886
02:42:00,377 --> 02:42:04,507
Ladies and gentlemen, I have here the
decision of our distinguished judges.

1887
02:42:04,748 --> 02:42:07,308
We will start with the award
for third prize.

1888
02:42:07,951 --> 02:42:10,283
For this honor,
the judges have named...

1889
02:42:10,520 --> 02:42:15,150
...the first soloist of the choir
of St. Agatha's Church in Murback.

1890
02:42:15,425 --> 02:42:17,655
Fräulein Schweiger.

1891
02:42:54,531 --> 02:42:58,490
Second prize
to The Toby Reiser Quintet.

1892
02:43:26,496 --> 02:43:30,660
And the first prize,
the highest honor in all Austria...

1893
02:43:30,901 --> 02:43:33,995
...the von Trapp Family Singers.

1894
02:43:46,349 --> 02:43:48,044
The family von Trapp.

1895
02:44:02,632 --> 02:44:03,724
They're gone!

1896
02:44:22,419 --> 02:44:23,818
Come with me.

1897
02:44:27,657 --> 02:44:29,648
Quickly, quickly.

1898
02:44:30,594 --> 02:44:32,789
I have a place you can hide.

1899
02:44:33,530 --> 02:44:36,761
Slowly, slowly.

1900
02:44:47,777 --> 02:44:49,472
Open this gate.

1901
02:44:50,614 --> 02:44:52,172
Good evening.

1902
02:44:54,684 --> 02:44:56,174
Hurry up, woman.

1903
02:45:16,006 --> 02:45:17,200
Two men in there.

1904
02:45:17,440 --> 02:45:19,305
Six of you cover the yard.

1905
02:45:19,509 --> 02:45:21,807
You two, cover the corridor.

1906
02:45:36,293 --> 02:45:39,854
Reverend Mother, we didn't realize
we put the abbey in this danger.

1907
02:45:40,130 --> 02:45:42,655
No, Maria, it was right for you
to come here.

1908
02:45:42,866 --> 02:45:44,731
We thought we might borrow
your car.

1909
02:45:44,968 --> 02:45:46,856
I'm afraid our car will do you
no good now.

1910
02:45:47,470 --> 02:45:49,131
I've been listening to the wires.

1911
02:45:49,339 --> 02:45:51,830
The borders have just been closed.

1912
02:45:57,714 --> 02:45:59,978
All right,
if the borders are closed...

1913
02:46:01,251 --> 02:46:04,607
...then we'll drive up into the hills
and go over the mountains on foot.

1914
02:46:05,188 --> 02:46:07,179
- The children--
- We'll help them.

1915
02:46:07,424 --> 02:46:09,619
We can do it without help, Father.

1916
02:46:10,694 --> 02:46:12,059
Maria.

1917
02:46:12,729 --> 02:46:15,391
You will not be alone.
Remember:

1918
02:46:15,632 --> 02:46:18,692
"I will lift up mine eyes unto
the hills from whence cometh my help."

1919
02:46:19,703 --> 02:46:20,761
Yes, Mother.

1920
02:46:22,172 --> 02:46:24,333
- I'm scared.
- Me too.

1921
02:46:36,419 --> 02:46:37,579
God be with you.

1922
02:46:44,527 --> 02:46:46,051
- Mother.
- Yes?

1923
02:46:46,296 --> 02:46:49,527
Would it help if we sang
about our favorite things?

1924
02:46:49,766 --> 02:46:52,758
No, darling.
This is one time it would not help.

1925
02:46:53,036 --> 02:46:56,233
You must be very quiet.
Hold tight to me.

1926
02:49:10,840 --> 02:49:12,034
Let's try the roof.

1927
02:50:08,298 --> 02:50:10,596
Rolfe, please.

1928
02:50:15,638 --> 02:50:17,162
No, wait.

1929
02:50:26,950 --> 02:50:28,315
Maria.

1930
02:50:29,419 --> 02:50:30,818
Children.

1931
02:50:34,891 --> 02:50:37,917
It's you we want, not them.

1932
02:50:38,294 --> 02:50:39,989
Put that down.

1933
02:50:41,097 --> 02:50:44,396
Not another move,
or I'll shoot.

1934
02:50:46,102 --> 02:50:48,127
You're only a boy.

1935
02:50:51,140 --> 02:50:54,803
- You don't really belong to them.
- Stay where you are.

1936
02:50:56,546 --> 02:50:58,537
Come away with us.

1937
02:50:59,816 --> 02:51:00,976
Before it's too late.

1938
02:51:01,551 --> 02:51:03,917
Not another step.
I'll kill you.

1939
02:51:06,189 --> 02:51:09,488
- You give that to me, Rolfe.
- Did you hear me?

1940
02:51:10,526 --> 02:51:12,118
I'll kill you.

1941
02:51:13,997 --> 02:51:15,487
Rolfe.

1942
02:51:33,816 --> 02:51:35,181
You'll never be one of them.

1943
02:51:37,954 --> 02:51:39,649
Lieutenant!

1944
02:51:39,889 --> 02:51:41,015
They're here!

1945
02:51:41,224 --> 02:51:42,748
They're here, lieutenant!

1946
02:52:24,100 --> 02:52:25,727
Reverend Mother.

1947
02:52:27,070 --> 02:52:28,867
I have sinned.

1948
02:52:30,073 --> 02:52:32,200
I too, Reverend Mother.

1949
02:52:33,876 --> 02:52:36,140
What is this sin, my children?

1950
02:53:02,438 --> 02:53:05,771
<i>A dream that will need</i>

1951
02:53:05,942 --> 02:53:11,471
<i>All the love you can give</i>

1952
02:53:12,081 --> 02:53:15,573
<i>Every day of your life</i>

1953
02:53:15,752 --> 02:53:21,748
<i>For as long as you live</i>

1954
02:53:23,059 --> 02:53:27,814
<i>Climb every mountain</i>

1955
02:53:28,264 --> 02:53:32,963
<i>Ford every stream</i>

1956
02:53:33,136 --> 02:53:37,960
<i>Follow every rainbow</i>

1957
02:53:38,207 --> 02:53:42,530
<i>Till you find</i>

1958
02:53:42,712 --> 02:53:50,278
<i>Your dream</i>

1959
02:54:32,595 --> 02:54:34,586
[ENGLISH]

